1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arises after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2. e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ White opts for a closed game. This is a popular approach. The alternative  3.Nf3  leads to the Three Knights. }
3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nf3
{ This is White's most popular and challenging move. It accounts for more than half of the games in the Pure Symmetrical. }
5... e5
{ We will go for the reversed Botvinnik setup. It is solid, yet ambitious. Black grabs space at the cost of weakening the d5-square. Decades of practice have shown that Black can get away with this. In fact, he can usually fight for d5 - after all, he has the same pieces to control it with that White does! }
6. O-O
{ Deviations from this move such as  6.d3  and  6.a3  are covered in the first chapter of this course. }
6... d6 7. a3
{ Another move order would be  7.d3  Nge7  8.a3   8.Ne1  Be6  is the 7.Ne1 line as covered here.  8...a5  9.Ne1   9.Rb1  O-O  reaches the 7. d3 lines from Chapter 2.  9...Be6  10.Nc2 }
7... a5
{ I used to think that this was a concession, as White has not had to spend a tempo on Rb1 yet. Black has recently shown that his position is quite viable anyway.   Instead,  7...Nge7  8.b4  transposes to 6... Nge7 7. a3 d6 8. b4 - a pleasant line for White that we are avoiding. }
8. Ne1 Be6
{ The point of the 6... d6 move order.   Not  8...Nge7  9.Nc2  Be6  10.Ne3  with an edge for White, as we have seen before. }
9. d3
{ After  9.Nd5  Nge7  10.Nc2  O-O  11.d3  we reach 10. Nd5 which is covered here. }
9... Nge7 10. Nc2
{ White allows the ...d5 break counting on the fact that he has not bothered to spend a tempo on Rb1 to allow him to develop some initiative.   10.Nd5  is possible, but this the 'wrong knight' - White wants to play Nc2-e3-d5.  10...O-O  11.Nc2  Rb8!  12.b4  axb4  12...b5!?  13.axb4  cxb4  14.Ncxb4  Nxb4  15.Nxb4  d5= }
10... d5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Ne3
{ This position is 'supposed to be' good for White. } 12... Nb6
{ This move has revitalized Black's whole concept. Black is holding, but our move is more challenging for White to meet.  The thematic   12...Nde7  is three times more common, but White has better chances of an edge here. The addition of the moves a3 &...a5 benefits White, as the b6- and b5-squares are weakened. }
13. Bxc6+
{ This is White's main try, and probably the most challenging move. White gives up his proud bishop to wreck the black structure. Here the addition of a3+... a5 favors Black, as White's light squares, particularly b3, have been weakened. }
13... bxc6
{ Black's structure is wrecked, but White had to give up his king's best defender. Both sides should keep an eye on Black's breaks with ...c4 and ...e4, even as pawn sacrifices. Find more details in Chapter 4. }
