[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arises after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2. e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ White opts for a closed game. This is a popular approach. The alternative  3.Nf3  leads to the Three Knights. }
3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. a3
{ This little move is actually second in popularity only to 5. Nf3. White simply wants to play the thematic Rb1, b4, and he wants to do it right away! }
5... d6
{ I have always played this way.   If  5...e5  6.b4!  as we have weakened the d6-square and the a3-f8 diagonal. We already saw Black avoiding this kind of thing in the 5. Nf3 lines.   The immediate  5...a5!?  feels a bit premature, considering White is very well likely to play  Rb1  next anyway. It is certainly feasible, however, and White's most common response is  6.Nf3  when  6...d6  7.O-O  e5  reaches the main lines of  5. Nf3.   Black can also play  5. ..a6  6.Rb1  Rb8  7.b4  cxb4  8.axb4  b5  9.cxb5  axb5  Now White has to commit something. I looked at  10.Nf3  e5  11.d4!  exd4  12.Nd5  Nf6  13.Bg5  and found it difficult to get excited about Black's extra pawn.   Other good moves are  5...e6  and  5...Nf6  but they are not related to our repertoire. }
6. Rb1 a5 { With the idea  7.Nf3  e5  and a transposition, but... } 7. d3 e5 8.
e4
{ This is a 'double Botvinnik' where the queenside structure favours White, but it should still be equal.   The more common  8.Nf3  Nge7  9.O-O  O-O  and  8.e3  Nge7  9.O-O  O-O  just lead to the 5. Nf3 and 5. e3 lines. }
8... Nge7 9. Nge2 O-O 10. O-O Rb8 11. Be3 Be6 12. Nd5
{ This is a typical response to ...Be6 because Black cannot capture with the knight. It also supports b2-b4. }
12... b5
{ But moving the knight from c3 also allows Black to play this break. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Quide"]
[Black "Pure Symmetrical: 5.e4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arises after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2. e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ White opts for a closed game. This is a popular approach. The alternative  3.Nf3  leads to the Three Knights. }
3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. e4
{ Trying to use our own weapons against us! Well, we know White can equalize and get an interesting game, but that's ok. }
5... Nf6
{ I am going to show a way of playing that I accidentally invented when playing a very strong former student of mine. }
6. Nge2 O-O
{ There are various move orders. Sometimes Black tries  6...d6  with the idea  7.O-O  h5!?   White could just play the more accurate  7.d3  though. }
7. d3 d6 8. O-O a6 9. h3 Rb8 10. a4 Bd7 11. Be3 e5
{ I made this up at the board, and it's pretty good! This move is also not considered in Marin's series on the English Opening for White. We now have a 'double Botvinnnik' of sorts, but Black's knight is on the f6-square. It could be considered to be misplaced, but I do not think matters are so simple.   In this structure, pushing the f-pawn is not always so great, as a subsequent exf5/...exf4 opens the diagonal for a blocked bishop. Decades of playing the Botvinnik setup has also taught me to be careful with the e7-knight, as it is not always so manoeuvrable. The f6-knight has potential pathways to improvement, most notably with ...Ne8-c7.   Lastly, in this pawn structure, the move Be3/Be6 can be premature, as Nd5/...Nd4 can be annoying because capturing with a knight would lose a piece. Here White's bishop is already on e3, while our bishop is on the d7-square. I know sometimes this means it's more passive, but here I'll say it's more flexible! }
12. f4 { It's good to see how to play after this. } 12... exf4 13. Nxf4 Ne8
{ From here the Knight will go to c7, when it may trade off a knight on d5, or come to e6 and d4. Black is in good shape as can be seen here. }
