1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arises after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2. e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 4. e3
{ This has always been considered critical. White revs up for d4-d5 kicking the c6-knight. }
4... Nf6
{ Black avoids  4...Bg7  5.d4  when d4-d5 will kick the knight. This is playable but risky. }
5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3 Nxc3
{ Here  8...Nb6?  is out of the question because  9.d5  forces the pathetic  9...Nb8  .   Black does have a solid alternative in  8...e6!?  which has also become popular recently. }
9. Bc4 Nd5 10. Bxd5 e6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. O-O Qd5 13. Qc3
{ I have played this myself a few times. } 13... f6 14. Be3
{ 14.Bf4  looks more active, but the bishop is a target here, and indeed Black can immediately play  14...g5! }
14... Be7
{ 14...a5?!  15.Nd2  Bb4  16.Qc2  Kf7  17.Ne4  Ba6  18.Rfc1  Rhc8  19.f3!  gave White an ideal setup in Vigorito - Lenderman, Philadelphia 2013. }
15. Rfc1 Bd7 16. Ne1 Kf7 17. Nd3 Rab8
{ With chances for both sides. A few practical games are discussed here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Quide"]
[Black "Four Knights - 6.g3 Qb6 7.Nb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arises after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2. e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6 6. g3
{ This typical 'English' move has traditionally been the main line. } 6... Qb6
{ This direct attack aims to throw White off balance. The d4-knight is attacked, but often Black will play ...Ne5, hitting the c4-pawn, and also creating the possibility of ...Qc6. The ensuing play can be quite varied and there is quite a bit of theory here. A lot of the positions are fun and Black has his share of the chances. We will see a lot of ideas repeated for both sides. It is not uncommon for White to offer up the c4-pawn for an initiative, so do not sell your soul to win this pawn. The knight moves ...Ne5 and ...Nfg4 are typical for Black, as is the counterstrike ...g5 in certain positions with a white bishop on f4. }
7. Nb3
{ The knight is secure here, and it also supports a potential c4-c5 advance. Black should always watch for this move, even if it's a pawn sacrifice. }
7... Ne5 { This does not only attack the c4-pawn, but it sets up ...Qc6. } 8.
e4 Bb4 { Black develops quickly and puts pressure on the e4-pawn. } 9. Qe2
{ This is the main line. White protects the e4-pawn, and also covers the c4-pawn to prepare Bg2. }
9... d6
{ Bringing some protection to the dark squares. Black has to time ... Bxc3 carefully, because if the capture is done too early White will be able to play Ba3 and the bishop will slice through Black's position. Now White chooses between immediate aggression in the center or the prevention of doubled pawns. }
10. f4 { This is the older line. } 10... Nc6
{ Simply retreating is best.   10...Bxc3+?  11.bxc3  Nc6  12.Ba3!  is something to avoid. }
11. Be3
{ With this move White prepares castling kingside. Other moves leave the g1-a7 diagonal open, and after so many pawn advances White's king can easily become exposed. }
11... Bxc3+ { Now that there is no Ba3, it's time to smash the pawns. } 12.
bxc3 Qc7 13. Bg2 e5
{ Blocking e4-e5 and taking a stand on the dark-squares. If allowed, Black will follow up with ...b6 to prevent c4-c5. Then ...Be6 or ...Ba6 will lay siege to the c4-pawn.  Further moves are explored here. }
