[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arises after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2. e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6 6. g3
{ This typical 'English' move has traditionally been the main line. } 6... Qb6
{ This direct attack aims to throw White off balance. The d4-knight is attacked, but often Black will play ...Ne5, hitting the c4-pawn, and also creating the possibility of ...Qc6. The ensuing play can be quite varied and there is quite a bit of theory here. A lot of the positions are fun and Black has his share of the chances. We will see a lot of ideas repeated for both sides. It is not uncommon for White to offer up the c4-pawn for an initiative, so do not sell your soul to win this pawn. The knight moves ...Ne5 and ...Nfg4 are typical for Black, as is the counterstrike ...g5 in certain positions with a white bishop on f4. }
7. Ndb5
{ This is White's most aggressive option. The knight is a bit out on a limb, but we will see that White has a variety of tactical ideas. Typical ideas are Bf4, taking aim at the c7-square, Qa4, and Black always has to watch out for c4-c5. The lines can be varied and complicated, but Black is in good shape theoretically. }
7... Ne5
{ Just as it did against 7. Nb3, this attacks the c4-pawn and creates the possibility of ...Qc6. }
8. Bf4
{ This is the most forcing continuation. The knight cannot move because of Nc7+. }
8... Nfg4 { This defends the e5-knight and attacks the f2-pawn. } 9. e3
{ An obvious move, but we will see that White does not always have to prevent something from landing on the f2-square! After playing both e3 and g3, White must always watch out for ...g5 or ...e5 which could trap his bishop. }
9... a6 10. h3
{ This leads to an equal endgame... usually.   10.Qa4!?  This idea is the trickiest.  10...Ra7!  A strange move which Black has to know! }
10... axb5 11. hxg4 Nxc4 12. Qb3
{ 12.Rc1  was Giri's recent try.  12...d5  13.b3  Bb4  14.bxc4  Ra3  Giri was moving very quickly here. it was an interesting idea to check this because the computer likes Black for quite a while, meaning black players probably did not pay much attention to it. }
12... d5 13. Bxc4 dxc4 14. Qxb5+ Qxb5 15. Nxb5 Ra5
{ This is less common than the alternative  15...Bb4+  but it looks cleaner to me. }
16. Nd6+ Bxd6 17. Bxd6 e5 { Black holds the balance as shown here. } *

