[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arises after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2. e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6 6. a3
{ This little prophylactic move is second in popularity, with almost as many games played as 6.g3. White takes a move to prevent ...Bb4 while maintaining maximum flexibility. While 6.g3 presents more of a memory challenge, 6.a3 makes it more difficult for Black to create active counterplay. }
6... Be7
{ There are other options, but with ...Bb4 off the table, I like this simple developing move. }
7. e4
{ This is the most popular move. White wants to play a Hedgehog, even though he has already spent a move on 6. a3.   I am not a big Hedgehog player, but I know that usually, Black does not put a knight on c6 @@StartBracket@@...Nbd7 would be more typical@@EndBracket@@. Because of these two factors, I believe Black should play rather directly because ...Nc6 is a developing move while a3 was not!   7.g3  This looks a bit odd to me.  7...Qb6!  Now this works out rather well, as it does in the main lines with 6. g3 Qb6. }
7... O-O
{ Now Black is hoping to play ...d5 when White does not have his Hedgehog, but Black does have his developpment lead. }
8. Nf3
{ This is the main move. White prevents ...d5 and keeps his knight on an active square where it helps control the center. }
8... Qc7 { This prevents Bf4 and is Black's main response. } 9. Be2
{ The main move. } 9... b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. Bg5
{ This non-pin is White's most popular move. } 11... Ne5
{ This direct move is a favourite of MVL. Instead  11...h6  is more popular, but considering the bishop usually retreats to h4 anyway, why should we bother?  A bunch of rook moves are also playable:  11...Rac8  ,  11...Rfd8  , and  11...Rad8  for example. }
12. Nxe5
{ 12.Nd2  Ng6!  intending ...h6, is already nice for Black. In fact, White has not yet scored from this position in three games. }
12... Qxe5 { Hitting the g5-bishop as well as the e4-pawn. } 13. Bh4 Rac8
{ This is a novelty, and is further explained here. } *

