{ This is more critical than greedy pawn grabbing with  7.cxd5  .  There's a little threat with Nc7+, so Black's reply is forced. }
7... e5 8. cxd5 exf4 9. dxc6 bxc6
{ We cannot trade queens ourselves because Nc7+ would still hang over our head. So we have to allow our King to be displaced. }
10. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is an important position. Black's King is a little bit exposed and his pawn structure is broken. However, he has the Bishop-pair and open lines for his rooks.   It's dynamically equal, and Black has decent chances of taking the initiative. }
11. Rd1+
{ This is the most common choice. White activates the Rook but keeps the f2-pawn guarded. Black has more than one way to equalize.   11.Nd4  This simple retreat used to be uncommon, but it's not totally harmless.  11...Bd7!?  I like this move the best. MVL has played 11...Bb7, but this blocks the b-file and I don't think it's so easy for Black. 11...Kc7 is flexible though, and not a bad alternative.   11.O-O-O+  This is very natural. White gets the rook to the d-file with tempo, secures his king, and protects the b2-pawn - all in one move. But there is a downside - the f2-pawn is a glaring weakness.  11...Ke7!?  This modern move was likely rejected for a long time because of its clumsy appearance. However, the king is quite safe here, and ... g6 will soon take care of the f8-bishop. Black has done very here, and engines are already favouring Black. }
11... Bd7
{ Here  11...Ke7  is not as good. After  12.Nd4  Bd7  13.g3  we do not have ...Ng4 with such effect because the f2-pawn is covered, so Black lacks counterplay. }
12. Nd6
{ Black quickly obtains the initiative after  12.Nd4?!  Kc7  13.g3  Rb8  with ...Bb4 coming. }
12... Kc7
{ I like this active pawn sacrifice, which maintains the Bishop-pair. Instead  12...Bxd6  13.Rxd6  Rb8  is the main line. White can secure the b-pawn with  14.b3  or  14.Rd2  and aspire for a tiny advantage. }
13. Nxf7 Rg8
{ Now White can extract his Knight, or get going with his kingside development. }
14. Ne5 { 14.g3  Rb8!  There is no need to exchange on g3 yet. } 14... Rb8
{ Black has to play for activity! } 15. Nxd7
{ This eliminates Black's Bishop-pair and avoids losing more time with the e5-Knight. }
15... Nxd7 16. g3
{ White looks to catch up in development rather than worrying about the b2-pawn.   16.Rd2  protects the b2-pawn.  16...Ne5  With the idea ...Nc4. }
16... Rxb2 { White can easily go wrong here, as shown in Chapter 17. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Quide"]
[Black "Four Knights - 6.Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arises after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2. e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6 6. Bf4
{ This is a pretty serious move. It is the fourth most popular after  6.g3  ,  6.a3  , and  6.Ndb5  . }
6... d5 7. e3 { 7.Ndb5  transposes to the 6.Ndb5 line. } 7... Bb4 8. Be2
{ 8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.Qa4  Qb6  10.Bd3  O-O  11.O-O  a5 } 8... dxc4
{ MVL has played four different moves here for Black! The engine says everything is equal, and this looks the most solid. }
9. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 10. Rxd1 bxc6
{ Black's pawns are broken, but he is ready to play ...Nd5 as shown here. } *

