1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arises after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2. e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6 6. e4
{ This position can also arise from the Taimanov Sicilian: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nc6  5.c4  . In fact, the ECO classification is as such B44.  However, White rarely plays this way via the Sicilian move order because it is not considered to be very promising for White, and this position is just as likely to arise from our English move order. }
6... Bc5
{ 6...Bb4  However, top players are not afraid to try it with White once in a while. It is probably equal, but it is hardly simple and after  7.Nxc6  bxc6  8.Bd3  e5  9.O-O  there are a lot of different things that White can try, and Black's play is hardly trivial. The text move is less common, but it looks like a much simpler solution to use against this somewhat uncommon line. }
7. Nxc6 dxc6 { 7...bxc6  8.e5  is just bad for Black. } 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Now Black wants to play ...e5 with a great pawn structure. } 9. Bf4
{ 9.f4  e5!  anyway!  10.fxe5  Ng4  11.Bf4  Re8=+ } 9... e5 10. Bxe5
{ 10.O-O-O+  Ke7  11.Bxe5  Ng4⇆  Black has good counterplay. } 10... Bxf2+ 11.
Kxf2 Ng4+ 12. Kg3 Nxe5 { with a great outpost and a favorable endgame. } *

