[Black "White avoids the Four Knights - 5.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arises after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2. e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. g3
{ This is a tricky move order if Black is not prepared. The main lines of the Four Knights have held up very well for Black for a long time, so White tries to avoid the main lines. }
5... e5 6. Nb5 Bb4+ 7. N1c3 d6 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. Nxc3
{ 9.bxc3  White tries to keep pressure on the d6-pawn.  9...O-O } 9... Be6
{ Black's 'Sveshnikov' structure may not appeal to some, but Black has such smooth development he is doing well. Even though White has the bishop pair Black shold not refrain from opening the position because White is not really ready for it. If White tends to his c4-pawn he can quickly come under pressure. }
10. Bg2
{ White does best to get caught up in development.   10.e4  This looks sensible, and it has been tried a few times. This has been tried a few times. White clamps on the d5-square and protects the c4-pawn, but he cannot play Bg2 without dropping it again.  10...O-O   10.Bg5!?  White offers a pawn to develop actively.  10...Bxc4  11.Bxf6  Qxf6  Giving back the pawn to equalize easily. Black could also try  12.Ne4  Qe6  13.Nxd6+  This is not a problem. Black is still ahead in development, after all.  13...Ke7  14.Nxc4  Qxc4  This position is level. }
10... Bxc4 11. Bg5 O-O 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. O-O
{ Rather than trading pieces to regain the pawn, White hopes to get some pressure with his active pieces.   13.Bxf6  Qxf6  14.Ne4  wins back the pawn, but does not bring White any advantage.  14...Qe6  15.Rxc4  Qxc4  16.Nxd6  Qa2  17.Nxc8  Rxc8  18.Qc1  Ne7  forces the white queen back to d1. }
13... Nd4 { Black also plays for activity. } 14. Bxb7 Rb8 15. Bd5 Nxd5
{ A cool sacrifice. } 16. Bxd8 Nxc3 17. bxc3 Nxe2+ 18. Kg2 Nxc1
{ With a sharp position. White needs to be careful as shown here. } *

