6. a3 { This is tricky. } 6... a5
{ 6...Nge7  7.O-O  takes us out of our repertoire, while  6...d6  7.b4!?  e4  8.Ne1  looks weird but it has scored well for White.  Now 7. O-O or 7. d3 would just lead to normal transpositions. White has an alternative however. }
7. d4
{ This is a shocking gambit which looks to exploit Black's pawn advances. }
7... cxd4 8. Nb5 d6 9. e3 { Black should return the pawn with } 9... Nge7
{ Black has also tried  9...Be6  10.b3  d5!?  which looks adequate as well. }
10. exd4 O-O
{ Black has good development and a stake in the center. The weakness of the b5-square, as usual, is not fatal. }
11. O-O { This is more testing. } 11... Bg4 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nf5
{ Maintaining the pawn structure, but  13...Nxd4!?  14.Nxd4  exd4  15.Qxb7  Rb8  is possible as well. }
14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Be3 Nfd4
{ Black could also consider simply taking the bishop. } 16. Bxd4 Nxd4
{ 16...exd4  16.c5  +/= gives White an outpost on  d6. } 17. Qxb7
{ 17.Nxd4  Qxd4  is just equal. } 17... Rb8 18. Qa6 Qc8 19. Qxa5 Nb3 20. Qb4
Nxa1 21. Rxa1 { White's queenside looks impressive, but } 21... e4 22. Bxe4
Qxh3
{ This position is unclear. Black does have open lines for his rooks after all, and ...h5-h4 is a possibility. }
*

