{ White has nothing better. Instead  9.b4?  loses a piece to  9...e4  -+ } 9...
a5 { Preventing b4. We have reached the main lines. } 10. Bg5 f6
{ We will pretty much always answer Bg5 this way. Black gets ...f6 'for free' which represents a trade off of sorts. The g7-bishop is blocked in even more and Black's position is slightly loosened up. The upside is that Black can play ...Be6 immediately as there is no Nf3-g5 to worry about.   If  10...h6  11.Bxe7  Qxe7  12.Ne1  White is well on his way to controlling the d5-square forever. }
11. Bd2 Be6
{ Compared to the immediate 10. Bd2, Black can play this straight away because there is no Nf3-g5. }
12. Ne1 d5 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Qb3
{ This is an attempt to justify White's play tactically, as ...f6 has left the e6-bishop loose. It all feels a bit artificial though, and with the knight on e1 White is less ready for a tactical fight. }
14... a4
{ Not  14...Nd4?  15.Bxd5!  Nxb3  16.Bxe6+  Kh8  17.Bxb3  ±   However,  14...Nc7  is a decent alternative which was played by Giri.  15.Qxb7   15.Qb6  Nd4  gave Black the initiative in Svidler - Giri, Moscow 2016  15...Nd4  with compensation. }
15. Qd1 { This is rather timid-looking. } 15... Nd4
{ Black could also play  15...Nb6!?  but it is at least as good to play the main move.   Now  16.Nxa4  transposes to the 15. Nxa4 line which is covered in the next variation. }
*

