a5 { Preventing b4. We have reached the main lines. } 10. Bg5 f6
{ We will pretty much always answer Bg5 this way. Black gets ...f6 'for free' which represents a trade off of sorts. The g7-bishop is blocked in even more and Black's position is slightly loosened up. The upside is that Black can play ...Be6 immediately as there is no Nf3-g5 to worry about.   If  10...h6  11.Bxe7  Qxe7  12.Ne1  White is well on his way to controlling the d5-square forever. }
11. Be3
{ This is one of White's most interesting alternatives to the standard Ne1 plans. The pressure on the c5-pawn hinders ... d5. }
11... Be6 12. Ne1
{ The knight cannot make its usual tour to e3 and d5, but from c2 it will help support the b4 break. }
12... Qd7 { If  12...Rb8  13.Nc2  and  b4 comes next. } 13. Nc2 Bh3
{ This is simplest. A decent alternative is the most common  13...a4!?  which leads to complicated positions. Now White should play  14.b4!  anyway. The b-file pressure makes up for the weak a3-pawn.  14...axb3  15.Rxb3  Rab8  This was all considered nice for White due to the attractive game that continued  15...Rfb8  16.Qb1  in the well-known game Andersson - Seirawan, Linares 1983. Here I would suggest  16...f5!?  with the idea  17.Bg5  e4  with unclear play }
14. b4 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 axb4 16. axb4 b6
{ Black is solid on the queenside and will play on the kingside. White has the better bishop, but his position is a bit passive. }
17. Bd2 f5 18. bxc5 bxc5 19. Ne3 f4
{ 19...Nb4  to control the d5-square is also possible. Then  20.Nc2  Nbc6  repeats. }
20. Ned5 Nxd5 21. Nxd5 Nd4 22. Nb6 { This could be met with } 22... Qd8
{ Or simply  22...Qc6+ } 23. Nxa8 f3+ 24. exf3 Qxa8
{ Black has obvious compensation. One possibility is } 25. Ra1 Qc6 26. Be3 Nxf3
27. Kh1 Nd2+ 28. Kg1 Nf3+ { with perpetual check. } *

