{ Black could also play  16...axb4  17.axb4  cxb4  reaching the next note.   Or the ambitious  16...b5!?  allowing  17.bxa5  in order to keep his pawn front. }
17. axb4 b6
{ This keeps some tension. Instead  17...axb4  18.Nxb4  Nxb4  19.Rxb4  Rfc8  is level after  20.Qb1  b5   or  20.Qb3  Qxb3  21.Rxb3  Rc2  22.Rd1  b5 }
18. Bc3 Rfd8 19. Ne3 Qe6 { After } 20. bxa5 bxa5 21. Nc4 Rxb1 22. Qxb1 e4 23.
Bxg7 exd3 24. exd3 { If  24.Ba1  dxe2  25.Re1  Qxc4  with a winning position }
24... Kxg7 25. Nxa5 Nd4 26. Qb7
{ This was Altounian - Yermolinsky, San Diego 2004. Now } 26... Ne2+ 27. Kg2
Rxd3
{ Despite the symmetry and reduced material, Black is winning according to the engines. The a5-knight is in some trouble and White's king is not safe. }
*

