a5 { Preventing b4. We have reached the main lines. } 10. Ne1
{ This is a very common position where Black has done very well. White begins his knight tour, but after this Black will not have to bother with ...h6 because there is no Nf3-g5. }
10... Be6 { Black is all set to play ...d5. } 11. Nd5
{ Physically preventing ...d5. } 11... Rb8 { A familiar sight. } 12. Bg5 f6 13.
Bd2 b5 14. Nc2 b4 { or  14...bxc4!?  15.dxc4  a4 } 15. axb4 axb4 16. Ra1 f5
{ Normally we would not allow Bg5, but White's play has been very slow with his knight moves and Ra1-b1-a1.   16...Bc8!?  intending to take on  d5  looks fine too. }
17. Bg5 h6 18. Bxe7 Nxe7 19. Nxe7+ Qxe7 20. Ne3 e4
{ with counterplay. Now the following is a plausible continuation: } 21. dxe4
Bxb2 22. Ra6 Be5 23. exf5 gxf5 24. Nd5 Bxd5 25. Bxd5+ Kh8 26. e3
{ White has the better pawn structure, but we have that little b-pawn. } 26...
b3 { with obvious counter-chances. } *

