{ We will go for the reversed Botvinnik setup. It is solid, yet ambitious. Black grabs space at the cost of weakening the d5-square. Decades of practice have shown that Black can get away with this. In fact, he can usually fight for d5 - after all, he has the same pieces to control it with that White does!   5...Nf6  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  O-O  8.O-O  is solid theoretically, but rather safe and easy for White to play.   5...e6  is a great alternative, especially if White plays quietly.  6.d4  is certainly the most challenging option.  6...cxd4  7.Nb5  d5  8.cxd5  when Black can play the solid  8...exd5  accepting an isolated pawn in exchange for easy development or go for the more complicated  8...Qa5+  when it is not easy for White to regain the pawn, but he maintains some pressure.  Here the margin of error for both players can be rather small.In the Botvinnik we need to know a collection of ideas, and then the 'theory' will be much more digestible. White has two main ideas - to play for b2-b4 and to reroute his f3-knight towards the weakened d5-square, usually by means of Ne1-c2-e3. Often White will combine these plans. Black will generally play for ...d6-d5. If he achieves this he will have a space advantage in a 'Maroczy' structure. This advance is not always possible of course, in which case Black can look to play the ...b5 break instead, usually prefaced with ...Rb8. With the center rather secure, Black may also look to the kingside with moves like ...f7-f5 or ...Be6, ...Qd7, and ...Bh3. }
6. O-O d6
{ Move orders are important! The point of this move is to have ...Be6 available immediately to attack the c4-pawn. This gives us time to fight for the d5-square. }
7. d3
{ This is a very natural move, and you can expect to face it quite often especially from those players who are playing White's setup to 'avoid theory'. The immediate 7. a3! is the most challenging. }
7... Nge7 8. a3
{ This the most common. Pretty much all of White's plans are more dangerous with a3 and ...a5 thrown in. This is because b2-b4 may become possible at any time, and the advance ...a5 weakens the b6- and b5-squares in Black's position.   8.Ne1  Be6  transposes to  7. Ne1. }
8... O-O
{ We could also play  8...a5  transposing to the  7. a3 lines, but there is no need to yet, as we will see. }
9. Rb1
{ White has nothing better. Instead  9.b4?  loses a piece to  9...e4  -+ } 9...
a5 { Preventing b4. We have reached the main lines. } 10. Ne1
{ This is a very common position where Black has done very well. White begins his knight tour, but after this Black will not have to bother with ...h6 because there is no Nf3-g5. }
10... Be6 { Black is all set to play ...d5. } 11. Nc2
{ White allows a Maroczy structure. This is the critical way to play - but it's more challenging if White has saved on the move Rb1. }
11... d5 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Ne3 Nde7
{ This could be considered an ideal retreat. The knights are well protected so it's easy to play moves like ...b6 to consolidate Black's space advantage. Black scores around 60% here! Compared to the 7. a3 a5 8. Ne1 line as in chapter 4, White has played the relatively unimportant Rb1 while Black has castled, so this retreat is safe enough for Black. }
14. Nc4 Rb8 15. Bg5 f6
{ Almost universally played.   15...h6!?  16.Bxc6  hxg5  with the idea ...g4 is good too. }
16. Be3 b6
{ Black is spoiled for choice:  16...b5  17.Nd2  Nd4  18.a4  b4  19.Nce4  Nd5!  Suggested by John Bartholomew!  20.Nxc5  Nxe3  21.fxe3  Bh6!  22.Nxe6  Bxe3+  23.Kh1  Nxe6  24.Nc4  Bh6=   16...Nd4  is also good.  17.b4?!  axb4  18.axb4  b5  19.Nd2  cxb4  20.Rxb4  Qa5  21.Qb1  was Anand - Tregubov, Bastia rapid 2014. Now  21...Nc2!  would have been strong.   16...Nd4  17.f4?!  b5  18.Nd2  was Anastasian - Jianchou Zhou, Moscow 2007, and here  18...Bh6!  would leave White tied up.   White should settle for  16...Nd4  17.a4  b6= }
17. f4 Nd5
{ Black has several good moves here. Others are  17...Bh6  ,  17...f5  and  17...b5!? }
18. f5 { Black has an easier time after the alternatives. } 18... gxf5 19. Nxd5
Bxd5 20. Bxd5+ Qxd5 21. Rxf5 Qe6
{ Other good options are  21...Ne7  22.Rf2  Qe6   or even  21...b5!?  22.Nd2  Nd4  23.Bxd4  Qxd4+  24.Kg2  c4  with counterplay. }
22. Qf1 { To maintain control over the f5-square. } 22... e4
{ with counterplay. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: Pure Symmetrical - 5.Nf3 with 7.a3"]
[Black "10.Nd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arise after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2.e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ White opts for a closed game. This is a popular approach. The alternative  3.Nf3  leads to the Three Knights. }
3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nf3
{ This is White's most popular and challenging move. It accounts for more than half of the games in the Pure Symmetrical. }
5... e5
{ We will go for the reversed Botvinnik setup. It is solid, yet ambitious. Black grabs space at the cost of weakening the d5-square. Decades of practice have shown that Black can get away with this. In fact, he can usually fight for d5 - after all, he has the same pieces to control it with that White does!   5...Nf6  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  O-O  8.O-O  is solid theoretically, but rather safe and easy for White to play.   5...e6  is a great alternative, especially if White plays quietly.  6.d4  is certainly the most challenging option.  6...cxd4  7.Nb5  d5  8.cxd5  when Black can play the solid  8...exd5  accepting an isolated pawn in exchange for easy development or go for the more complicated  8...Qa5+  when it is not easy for White to regain the pawn, but he maintains some pressure.  Here the margin of error for both players can be rather small.In the Botvinnik we need to know a collection of ideas, and then the 'theory' will be much more digestible. White has two main ideas - to play for b2-b4 and to reroute his f3-knight towards the weakened d5-square, usually by means of Ne1-c2-e3. Often White will combine these plans. Black will generally play for ...d6-d5. If he achieves this he will have a space advantage in a 'Maroczy' structure. This advance is not always possible of course, in which case Black can look to play the ...b5 break instead, usually prefaced with ...Rb8. With the center rather secure, Black may also look to the kingside with moves like ...f7-f5 or ...Be6, ...Qd7, and ...Bh3. }
6. O-O d6 7. a3
{ Another move order would be  7.d3  Nge7  8.a3   8.Ne1  Be6  is the 7.Ne1 line as covered here.  8...a5  9.Ne1   9.Rb1  O-O  reaches the 7. d3 lines from Chapter 2.  9...Be6  10.Nc2 }
7... a5
{ I used to think that this was a concession, as White has not had to spend a tempo on Rb1 yet. Black has recently shown that his position is quite viable anyway.   Instead  7...Nge7  8.b4  transposes to  6... Nge7 7. a3 d6 8. b4 - a pleasant line for White that we are avoiding. }
8. Ne1 Be6
{ The point of the 6... d6 move order.   Not  8...Nge7  9.Nc2  Be6  10.Ne3  with an edge for White, as we have seen before. }
9. d3 { After  9.Nd5  Nge7  10.Nc2  O-O  11.d3  we reach 10. Nd5. } 9... Nge7
10. Nd5
{ is possible, but this is the 'wrong knight' - White ideally wants to play Nc2-e3-d5. }
10... O-O 11. Nc2 Rb8 { 11...a4  is possible too. } 12. b4
{ 12.Bg5  f6  13.Bd2  b5  is reaches the  10. Bg5 line. } 12... axb4
{ 12...b5!? } 13. axb4 cxb4 14. Ncxb4 Nxb4 15. Nxb4 d5
{ with good play for Black } *

