6. O-O d6 7. a3
{ Another move order would be  7.d3  Nge7  8.a3   8.Ne1  Be6  is the 7.Ne1 line as covered here.  8...a5  9.Ne1   9.Rb1  O-O  reaches the 7. d3 lines from Chapter 2.  9...Be6  10.Nc2 }
7... a5
{ I used to think that this was a concession, as White has not had to spend a tempo on Rb1 yet. Black has recently shown that his position is quite viable anyway.   Instead,  7...Nge7  8.b4  transposes to 6... Nge7 7. a3 d6 8. b4 - a pleasant line for White that we are avoiding. }
8. Ne1 Be6
{ The point of the 6... d6 move order.   Not  8...Nge7  9.Nc2  Be6  10.Ne3  with an edge for White, as we have seen before. }
9. d3 { After  9.Nd5  Nge7  10.Nc2  O-O  11.d3  we reach 10. Nd5. } 9... Nge7
10. Nc2
{ White allows the ...d5 break counting on the fact that he has not bothered to spend a tempo on Rb1 to allow him to develop some initiative. }
10... d5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Ne3
{ This position is 'supposed to be' good for White. } 12... Nb6
{ This move has revitalized Black's whole concept. The thematic   12...Nde7  is three times more common, but White has better chances of an edge here. The addition of the moves  a3 &...a5  (benefits White, as the b6- and b5-squares are weakened.)   13.Nc4  O-O  14.Bg5  f6  15.Be3  b6  16.Qa4  and  f4  . I think Black is actually ok here, but he will have to be more careful.  16...Qc7   16...Rc8  17.Qb5!  17.f4  Rab8  18.fxe5  Nxe5  when White chooses between  19.Nxe5  and  19.Bf4  Black is holding, but  12...Nb6  is more challenging for White to meet. }
13. Bxc6+
{ This is White's main try, and probably the most challenging move. White gives up his proud bishop to wreck the black structure. Here the addition of a3 and ...a5 favors Black, as White's light squares, particularly b3, have been weakened. }
13... bxc6
{ Black's structure is wrecked, but White had to give up his king's best defender. Both sides should keep an eye on Black's breaks with ...c4 and ...e4, even as pawn sacrifices. }
14. Ne4 c4
{ Giving the pawn in this way increases Black's control over the light squares. }
15. dxc4 O-O 16. b3 a4 17. Qxd8 Rfxd8 18. Ng5 Bc8 19. b4 Ba6 20. c5 Nc4
{ This has been played in some correspondence games. Less accurate is  20...Nd5  21.Nxd5  Rxd5  22.Ra2!  += }
21. Ra2 h6 22. Ne4 f5 23. Nc3 Nxe3 24. fxe3
{ This is ugly, but the pawns control the center, and White may want to play Kf2 to cover the e-pawn at some point. }
24... e4
{ This sets some traps. Another move order is  24...Bc4  25.Rc2  Bb3  26.Rd2  e4  27.Nb1  which would transpose. }
25. Nb1
{ This is forced. Other moves lose material. For example  25.Bb2?  Rd2  or  25.Bd2?  Rxd2  . }
25... Bc4 26. Rd2 { This drops a pawn. } 26... Rxd2 27. Bxd2 Bxe2
{ Black has a huge advantage. } *

