1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arise after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2.e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ White opts for a closed game. This is a popular approach. The alternative  3.Nf3  leads to the Three Knights. }
3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. e3
{ This is not so common nowadays, but it is an important setup to be familiar with. }
5... e5
{ Sticking with the program.  5...e6  tends to lead to sterile equality, which is one reason why 5. e3 is not so popular among top players.   5...Bxc3!?  with the idea ...d6, ... Qd7, ...b6, ...Bb7 is an interesting way to imbalance the game. White can capture with either pawn. Black's argument is that the e3-pawn blocks the c1-bishop, so he will have time to arrange his pawns on dark squares without any tactical problems. I could easily have recommended this move, but one, it's not so easy to analyse systematically - it would be better to just look at a bunch of games. Two, for various transpositional reasons, we would need another system. As we will see later White may also reach e3 setups via the moves 5. a3, 5. d3, or even 5. b3. }
6. Nge2 Nge7 7. O-O O-O 8. a3 a5
{ We will consider this as the main line, because it is, and because we may reach these lines from other move orders. It turns out though that Black can play without this advance as well. For example:   8...d6  9.b4  Rb8!?  10.b5  Na5  11.d3  b6=   8...d6  9.Rb1  Be6  10.Nd5  Rb8  11.Nec3   11.b4  cxb4  12.axb4  b5=  a6!  12.b4  cxb4  13.axb4  b5= }
9. d3 d6 10. Rb1 Rb8
{ Always useful!   10...Be6?!  is a tempo short:  11.Nd5  Rb8  12.Nec3  +/= White is clamping down on both the d5- and b5-squares.  Now Black is ready to play ...Be6 and he can meet Nd5 with ...b5. If White plays Nd5 before ...Be6, Black can always capture without losing a piece. }
11. Bd2 Be6 { Both  11...Bf5!?  and  11...b6!?  are possible as well. } 12. Nd5
Bf5
{ By far the main move is  12...b5  13.cxb5  Rxb5  14.Nec3  Rb8  15.Qa4  Black would be a bit concerned about his queenside - like the  a5  -pawn, but it seems that  15...Bd7  is fine. However, it is hard to avoid a repetition after  16.Qc4  Be6  17.Qa4 }
13. Qc2 Nxd5
{ Also possible is  13...b5  14.cxb5  Rxb5  15.Nec3  Rb8  when White cannot play  16.Qa4?  Bxd3 }
14. cxd5 Na7 { A bit unconventional, but there is a concrete idea in mind. }
15. b4 Nb5 16. Ra1 e4
{ Provocative, but it looks good. There is also  16...axb4  17.axb4  b6= } 17.
dxe4 Bg4 18. f3 Bxa1 19. bxc5 Bg7 20. fxg4 dxc5 21. Qxc5 Qd7
{ Messy, but better for Black. } *

