1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arise after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2.e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ White opts for a closed game. This is a popular approach. The alternative  3.Nf3  leads to the Three Knights. }
3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. e4
{ Trying to use our own weapons against us! Well, we know White can equalize and get an interesting game, but that's ok. }
5... Nf6
{ I am going to show a way of playing that I accidentally invented when playing a very strong former student of mine.   5...a6!?  intending a quick  ...b5 is viable here, just as it is in reversed positions.   5...e5  is fine too of course, and probably a reason that  5. e4  is not so common. Most players want to fight for a little something with the White pieces! Here is an instructive example:  6.Nge2  Nge7  7.d3  d6  8.O-O  O-O  9.f4  exf4  10.Bxf4   10...Be6  11.Qd2  Qd7  12.Bh6  Rab8  13.Bxg7  Kxg7  14.Nd5  Bxd5  15.cxd5  Ne5  Collyer - Vigorito, Philadelphia 2003. It looks like Black just has a knight vs. bad bishop, but it will take some work to find the e7-knight a decent square.   10...Ne5!  would have been more accurate. Then the  e7-knight can head to c6 }
6. Nge2 O-O
{ There are various move orders. Sometimes Black tries  6...d6  with the idea  7.O-O  h5!?   White could just play the more accurate  7.d3  though. }
7. d3
{ This looks best - remember we played ... d6 quickly in the same setup with Black. }
7... d6
{ If  7...Ne8  8.Be3  d6  9.d4!  As we would do ourselves with colours reversed. }
8. O-O a6
{ Again avoiding  8...Ne8  9.Be3!  Nc7   or  9...Nd4  10.Rb1!  just as we would play in the reversed position.  10.d4 }
9. Rb1 Rb8 10. a3 b5 11. cxb5 axb5 12. b4 Ba6
{ Keeping control of  d4 maintains some dynamism rather than going for the sterile   12...cxb4  13.axb4  e5= }
13. h3 Nd7 14. Be3 Nd4 { With an interesting position. } *

