[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5: Pure Symmetrical - Other White 5th moves"]
[Black "5.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arise after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2.e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ White opts for a closed game. This is a popular approach. The alternative  3.Nf3  leads to the Three Knights. }
3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. a3
{ This little move is actually second in popularity only to 5. Nf3. White simply wants to play the thematic Rb1, b4, and he wants to do it right away! }
5... d6
{ I have always played this way.   If  5...e5  6.b4!  as we have weakened the d6-square and the a3-f8 diagonal. We already saw Black avoiding this kind of thing in the 5. Nf3 lines.   The immediate  5...a5!?  feels a bit premature, considering White is very well likely to play  Rb1  next anyway. It is certainly feasible, however, and White's most common response is  6.Nf3  when  6...d6  7.O-O  e5  reaches the main lines of  5. Nf3.   Black can also play  5. ..a6  6.Rb1  Rb8  7.b4  cxb4  8.axb4  b5  9.cxb5  axb5  Now White has to commit something. I looked at  10.Nf3  e5  11.d4!  exd4  12.Nd5  Nf6  13.Bg5  and found it difficult to get excited about Black's extra pawn.   Other good moves are  5...e6  and  5...Nf6  but they are not related to our repertoire. }
6. Rb1 a5
{ With the idea  7.Nf3  e5  and a transposition, but White has an alternative. }
7. d3 e5 8. e4
{ This is a 'double Botvinnik' where the queenside structure favours White, but it should still be equal. The more common  8.Nf3  Nge7  9.O-O  O-O   and  8.e3  Nge7  9.Nge2  O-O  just lead to the  5. Nf3 and 5. e3 lines, respectively. }
8... Nge7 9. Nge2 O-O 10. O-O Rb8
{ A high-level game saw very passive play from Black:  10...Bd7?!  11.Bd2  h6  12.Nb5  Be6  - wasting a tempo -  13.Nec3  b6  14.Nd5  +/=was So - Giri, Wijk aan Zee 2016. White is clamping down on everything. }
11. Be3
{ Or  11.Bd2  Be6  12.Nd5  b5=   An example from my own practice:  11.Bg5  f6  12.Bd2  b6  13.h3  Kh8  14.Kh2  Be6  15.g4?!  Qd7  16.f4  f5  =/+ was J.Chan - Vigorito, Somerville 2007. Black's rooks are connected and his king position is safer so he is more ready for the opening of the position. }
11... Be6
{ Another example of passive play to avoid:  11...Bd7?!  12.Qd2  Nd4  13.b4  axb4  14.axb4  b6  15.b5  Ra8  16.Qb2  Bg4  17.f3  Bc8  18.Bg5  Nxe2+  19.Qxe2  Bb7  Black has made four moves with this bishop to put it on a dead square.  20.Bh3  +/- was Seirawan - Anastasian, Groningen 1997. }
12. f4 Nd4 13. b4 axb4 14. axb4 b6
{ This position is just solid for both sides. Black may take on f4 at some point to open up his bishop. }
*

