11. Be3
{ Or  11.Bd2  Be6  12.Nd5  b5=   An example from my own practice:  11.Bg5  f6  12.Bd2  b6  13.h3  Kh8  14.Kh2  Be6  15.g4?!  Qd7  16.f4  f5  =/+ J.Chan - Vigorito, Somerville 2007. Black's rooks are connected and his king position is safer so he is more ready for the opening of the position. }
11... Be6
{ Another example of passive play to avoid:  11...Bd7?!  12.Qd2  Nd4  13.b4  axb4  14.axb4  b6  15.b5  Ra8  16.Qb2  Bg4  17.f3  Bc8  18.Bg5  Nxe2+  19.Qxe2  Bb7  Black has made four moves with this bishop to put it on a dead square.  20.Bh3  +/- was Seirawan - Anastasian, Groningen 1997. }
12. Nd5
{ This is a typical response to ...Be6 because Black cannot capture with the knight. It also supports b2-b4. }
12... b5
{ But moving the knight from c3 also allows Black to play this break. } *

