{ Instead  3...e5  would be nice to recommend, and indeed this is a favorite of one of our heroes - MVL. Now  4.g3  g6  would bring us to the Pure Symmetrical lines   However,  4.e3  is another story.  4...Nf6  and now the main line with  5.d4  cxd4  6.exd4  e4  is interesting at least   Instead White can play  5.Be2!?   or  5.a3!?  I think Black is more or less compelled to play  5...d5  with a Reversed Sicilian of sorts. If we wanted to play like that,  1...e5  would be a good start!   Unsurprisingly,  3...Nf6  is very solid. Then  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  e6  reaches the Four Knights, which would suit our purposes   However,  4.g3  is tricky. After  4...d5   4...g6  5.Bg2  Bg7  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  O-O  8.O-O  is a well-known position. I think that Black can gradually equalize here, but it's almost universally considered to be more pleasant for White.  5.d4!   there is also  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nc7  is the Rubinstein Variation - comfortable for Black, but there's an awful lot to know.  5...cxd4  6.Nxd4  dxc4  7.Nxc6  Qxd1+  8.Nxd1  bxc6  9.Bg2  Nd5  10.Ne3  e6  11.Nxc4  Ba6  is probably ok for Black, but it is kind of dreary, and White scores over 60% here. }
4. e3 Nf6
{ Black avoids  4...Bg7  5.d4  when d4-d5 will kick the knight. This is playable but risky. }
5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 { 6.Nxd4  Bg7  reaches the Maroczy Fail chapter. } 6... d5
7. Be2
{ This simple developing move is not very common in this exact position, but it is important to understand the positions that arise. }
7... Bg7 8. O-O O-O
{ Now we really have a reversed Tarrasch Defence to the Queen's Gambit Declined - @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Nf3  Nc6  6.g3  Nf6  7.Bg2  Be7  8.O-O  O-O  White is up a tempo, but in reversed positions this can be surprisingly unimportant as 'White' openings and 'Black' openings generally have different goals - White is fighting for the initiative while Black looks to neutralize it. Here White's extra tempo allows him to equalize, but no more.   In fact, Black scores very highly from this position. It could also arise from the Grünfeld: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.Nc3  d5  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.e3  O-O  6.Be2  c5  7.O-O  cxd4  8.exd4  Nc6  White has to make some move and then Black can try to choose a setup where the 'extra' move is relatively unimportant. }
9. h3
{ White uses his extra tempo for prophylaxis by ruling out ...Bg4, which would be the main move with colours reversed. }
9... Be6
{ I like this move and will consistently recommend it.  9...dxc4  and  9...b6  are quite decent alternatives }
10. c5 Ne4
{ In Grandmaster Repertoire 10: The Tarrasch Defence, Aagaard and Ntrilis consider this position reversed - @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Nf3  Nc6  6.g3  Nf6  7.Bg2  Be7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Be3  c4  10.Ne5  - and they give “  10...h6!  ”. Here the analogous move - h2-h3 - has already been played. So what should White do with the extra tempo? }
11. Be3 Nxc5 { A typical trick to remember. } 12. dxc5 d4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ Black will get the bishop pair and can be confident about the future. } 14.
Bf3 { 14.Rc1  Nf5!  N gives Black good play. } 14... Nxf3+
{ Another nice example for Black went  14...Rc8  15.Bd5  Bxd5  16.Bxd4  e5  17.Be3  Bc4  18.Qxd8  Rfxd8  19.Rfd1  f5  20.f3  Bf6  =/+ A.Adly-R. Ponomariov, Khanty-Mansiysk 2005. }
15. Qxf3 Qc8 { The idea is ...Qc6! } *

