4. e3 Nf6
{ Black avoids  4...Bg7  5.d4  when d4-d5 will kick the knight. This is playable but risky. }
5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 { 6.Nxd4  Bg7  reaches the Maroczy Fail chapter. } 6... d5
7. cxd5 Nxd5
{ This can also arise from the Caro-Kann: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.c4  Nf6  5.Nc3  Nc6  6.Nf3  g6  7.cxd5  Nxd5 }
8. Bc4 Nb6 9. Bb3 Bg7 10. Be3
{ This is a natural move, but it's purely defensive. White has an isolated pawn and Black is active, so it's really imperative that White fights for the initiative, else it will easily pass to Black. }
10... O-O 11. d5
{ One move after protecting the pawn, White 'changes his mind' and advances it. }
11... Na5 12. Bd4 Nxb3 13. Bxg7 Nxa1 14. Bxf8 Qxf8 15. Qxa1 Bg4
{ with a lead in development and a better pawn structure. } *

