7. cxd5 Nxd5
{ This can also arise from the Caro-Kann: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.c4  Nf6  5.Nc3  Nc6  6.Nf3  g6  7.cxd5  Nxd5 }
8. Bc4 Nb6 9. Bb3 Bg7 10. d5 Na5 11. O-O O-O
{ This usually arises from the English, but ECO considers it a Grunfeld. One move order would be @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.Nc3  d5  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.e3  O-O  6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.Bc4  Nb6  8.Bb3  c5  9.O-O  cxd4  10.exd4  Nc6  11.d5  Na5 }
12. h3
{ This is less common than  12.Re1  , but it is logical to prevent  ...Bg4  .   Instead  12.Bc2  Nac4!  is no problem for Black.   while  12.Bg5  Nxb3  13.axb3  Re8  14.Re1  Bg4  15.h3  Bxf3  16.Qxf3  transposes to a line covered after  12. Re1. }
12... Nxb3
{ This is straightforward, but  12...Re8  and  12...Bf5  have also been tried. }
13. axb3 e6
{ This has only been played a few times, and Black has not done well. But it's easy to improve on the games played. Instead  13...Bxc3  14.bxc3  Qxd5  is thematic and more common, but both  15.Qe2  and  15.Bd2!?  intending c4, give White good compensation. }
14. d6
{ If White does not go for this Black will eliminate the pawn and be better. }
14... Bd7 15. Bg5 f6 16. Be3 Rf7
{ This position is unclear, but I like Black's chances. He can continue with moves like ...Bf8, ...Nc8, ...Bc6 and perhaps ...e5.   Ideally Black would like to play  16...Bc6?!  , but after  17.Bc5  e5   perhaps Black had counted on  17...Nd7  , but  18.Bxa7!  b6  does not work because of  19.Nd4±  18.b4→  , White was doing well in Potkin - Alekseev, Tyumen 2012 }
