{ Black avoids  4...Bg7  5.d4  when d4-d5 will kick the knight. This is playable but risky. }
5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 { 6.Nxd4  Bg7  reaches the Maroczy Fail chapter. } 6... d5
7. cxd5 Nxd5
{ This can also arise from the Caro-Kann: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.c4  Nf6  5.Nc3  Nc6  6.Nf3  g6  7.cxd5  Nxd5 }
8. Bc4 Nb6 9. Bb3 Bg7 10. d5 Na5 11. O-O O-O
{ This usually arises from the English, but ECO considers it a Grunfeld. One move order would be @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  g6  3.Nc3  d5  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.e3  O-O  6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.Bc4  Nb6  8.Bb3  c5  9.O-O  cxd4  10.exd4  Nc6  11.d5  Na5 }
12. Re1 { The main line. } 12... Bg4
{ We will take the opportunity to pin the knight. Black has less space so it makes sense to exchange a set of minor pieces.  12...Nxb3  and  12...Re8  are also possible. }
13. Bg5 { A sharp alternative. } 13... Re8 14. d6
{ Initiating great complications. Instead  14.h3  Bxf3  heads back to the main line which we will get to later. }
14... Qxd6 { But not  14...Nxb3?  when White can play  15.Bxe7! } 15. Bxf7+
{ This is the point of White's play. } 15... Kxf7 16. Rxe7+
{ This wins Black's queen. Well, 'wins' may be a bit strong, as White has to give away most of his pieces. He will win some things back though, as Black has loose pieces all over the place - the g4-bishop and a5-knight for starters, but the rooks will come under attack as well! Really the g7-bishop is the only piece that is safe. }
16... Qxe7 17. Bxe7 Kxe7
{ White wins right away after  17...Rxe7??  18.Ng5+  . } 18. Nb5
{ This is the only move seen in GM practice, but it is inaccurate. } 18... Kf8
{ Run away! } 19. Qd6+ Kg8 20. Nc7 Red8 21. Qb4 Rac8
{ White cannot take everything at once. } 22. Qxg4
{ Instead  22.Qxa5  Rxc7  is much better for Black, as  ...Bxf3 destroying White's structure is a very real threat. }
22... Rxc7 { The rook and two minor pieces are stronger than the queen. } 23.
Re1
{ Completing development is better than lashing out with  23.Qe6+  Kh8  24.Ng5  Rf8  -/+, which favored Black even more in Tregubov - Kurnosov, Moscow 2008. }
23... Nc6
{ Black has coordinated his pieces and has a slight material advantage. } *

