{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arise after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2.e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5
{ White has three real approaches here: he can play 2. Nf3 with a quick d4; he can play 2. Nc3 and g3; finally, White can also play both knights out to keep us guessing. }
2. Nf3 Nc6
{ This will be our move order. Instead  2...Nf6  really would reduce our options.  I think 2... Nf6 is a good move if Black is aiming for a quick ...d5, which is a favorite method of Grunfeld players, or a Hedgehog setup with ...b6, a favorite of Nimzo/Queen's Indian players, in which case the c6-knight would not be well placed.   Another option is  2...g6  , but that allows White to set up a Maroczy Bind with  3.e4  Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Bg7  6.Be3  Having played both sides here, I consider this to be favorable for White. }
3. Nc3 g6
{ Instead  3...e5  would be nice to recommend, and indeed this is a favorite of one of our heroes - MVL. Now  4.g3  g6  would bring us to the Pure Symmetrical lines   However,  4.e3  is another story.  4...Nf6  and now the main line with  5.d4  cxd4  6.exd4  e4  is interesting at least   Instead White can play  5.Be2!?   or  5.a3!?  I think Black is more or less compelled to play  5...d5  with a Reversed Sicilian of sorts. If we wanted to play like that,  1...e5  would be a good start!   Unsurprisingly,  3...Nf6  is very solid. Then  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  e6  reaches the Four Knights, which would suit our purposes   However,  4.g3  is tricky. After  4...d5   4...g6  5.Bg2  Bg7  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  O-O  8.O-O  is a well-known position. I think that Black can gradually equalize here, but it's almost universally considered to be more pleasant for White.  5.d4!   there is also  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nc7  is the Rubinstein Variation - comfortable for Black, but there's an awful lot to know.  5...cxd4  6.Nxd4  dxc4  7.Nxc6  Qxd1+  8.Nxd1  bxc6  9.Bg2  Nd5  10.Ne3  e6  11.Nxc4  Ba6  is probably ok for Black, but it is kind of dreary, and White scores over 60% here. }
4. e3
{ This has always been considered critical. White revs up for d4-d5 kicking the c6-knight. }
4... Nf6
{ Black avoids  4...Bg7  5.d4  when d4-d5 will kick the knight. This is playable but risky. }
5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 { 6.Nxd4  Bg7  reaches the Maroczy Fail chapter. } 6... d5
7. cxd5 Nxd5
{ This can also arise from the Caro-Kann: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.c4  Nf6  5.Nc3  Nc6  6.Nf3  g6  7.cxd5  Nxd5 }
8. Qb3 Nxc3
{ Here  8...Nb6?  is out of the question because  9.d5  forces the pathetic  9...Nb8  .   Black does have a solid alternative in  8...e6!?  which has also become popular recently. }
9. Bc4 Nd5
{ This is a funny retreat, but it is the most ambitious move. Trying to hold on to the piece is out of the question:  9...Ne4?  10.Bxf7+  Kd7  11.Qe6+  Kc7  12.Qxe4  regains the piece with a winning position.   Black does have a solid alternative in  9...e6  10.bxc3  Bg7   10...Bd7  and  10...Na5  are also possible.  11.Ba3  Bf8  12.Bxf8  Kxf8  13.O-O  This position favours White, but only slightly. }
10. Bxd5 e6 11. Bxc6+
{ This is played 99% of the time. White gives away the bishop but secures the d4-pawn, and splits Black's pawns as well. The alternatives do not cause Black many problems. For example  11.Bc4  Bg7  12.d5  exd5  13.Bxd5  Qe7+!?  N  14.Be3  Qb4+=+  when the b2-pawn is weak, or  11.Be4  Bg7   11...Bb4+!?  12.Be3  Qa5+!?  N   12...O-O =  13.Bd2  Qa6  14.Bd3  Qb6=+  and here the d4-pawn is weak. }
11... bxc6 12. O-O
{ White has a development lead but Black has the Bishop-pair. Both sides have slight pawn weaknesses - on d4 and c6. I have played this with both colours. It's quite tricky! }
12... Qd5
{ Black centralizes the queen and increases his influence on the light squares.   The natural  12...Bg7?!  is not so good because after  13.Bf4  O-O  14.Qe3  White is ready to play Bf4-h6.   The immediate  12...f6!?  is also possible.  After 12... Qd5, White has many different ways to play. He can exchange queens himself, move his queen, or leave his queen and allow Black to make the exchange, although the second player is hardly obligated to do so.In general, we do not have to memorize too much here. It is more important to learn different plans and get a feel for the position. Black has to be a bit careful with his king, which will often take shelter on f7. White has to try to maintain some control of the position, as Black not only has the Bishop-pair but pawn play - with ...c5 as well as a potential advance of the kingside pawns. }
13. Bg5
{ There was a time when I thought that this move was very annoying, and I considered that 12... f6 may be more accurate than the more common 12... Qd5. The moves are practically interchangeable, but not here! }
13... Be7
{ I found this to be a surprising yet simple solution.  13...Bg7  14.Qe3!?  is the usual annoyance.  14...O-O  15.Bh6  +=   Instead  13...Qxb3  14.axb3  Bg7  15.Rfc1  O-O!?  is possible. As is often the case, both sides have pawn weaknesses. }
14. Bxe7
{ If White retreats his bishop, Black can play ...f6 and just be up a tempo with ...Be7 for free. }
14... Qxb3 15. axb3 Kxe7
{ Black has bad bishop, but in the exchange of dark-squared bishops has left White's pawns more exposed. }
16. Ne5 { White's knight heads to the ideal c5-square, but it's hardly fatal. }
16... Bd7 17. Nd3 Rhb8 18. Nc5 a5
{ Both sides have weaknesses. A possible line is } 19. Rfd1 Rb4 20. f3 Be8 21.
Kf2 f6 22. Ke3 g5 { with counterplay. } *

