13. Qe3
{ This rare move was recommended by Georgiev in his book on the English Opening for White. If Black plays ...f6, then Re1 can add pressure to the e6-square. }
13... Bb7
{ This has only been played once - in a correspondence game - as far as I can tell, but I think it's best. After the normal  13...f6  the common 14. Bd2 and 14. b3 do not bother Black much  but Georgiev 's  14.Nd2!  is indeed annoying. This is also a reason I avoided the  12 ...f6 move order.   After  14...Be7  15.Ne4  Kf7  16.Bd2  is a nice setup for White. }
14. Re1
{ Following Georgiev's recipe. After  14.Bd2  Black should avoid  14. ..Bg7?!  15.Bb4±  .   Better is  14...Rd8  or the computer's weird  14...Rg8!?  - I guess intending  ...g5!? }
14... Bg7
{ A correspondence game saw  14...c5  15.dxc5  Qxc5  16.Qf4  Bg7  17.Be3  Qb5  18.a4  Qf5  19.Qb4  Bxf3  20.gxf3  and White's initiative continued into the endgame.   Other possibilities are  14...Rd8  and the computer's amusing  14...Rg8!?  with a possible  ...g5 in the cards. }
15. Qa3 Bf8 16. Qc3 { 16.Qe3  Bg7  also repeats. } 16... Bg7
{ Black could also venture  16...f6!?  to avoid a repetition. } *

