{ Instead  3...e5  would be nice to recommend, and indeed this is a favorite of one of our heroes - MVL. Now  4.g3  g6  would bring us to the Pure Symmetrical lines   However,  4.e3  is another story.  4...Nf6  and now the main line with  5.d4  cxd4  6.exd4  e4  is interesting at least   Instead White can play  5.Be2!?   or  5.a3!?  I think Black is more or less compelled to play  5...d5  with a Reversed Sicilian of sorts. If we wanted to play like that,  1...e5  would be a good start!   Unsurprisingly,  3...Nf6  is very solid. Then  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  e6  reaches the Four Knights, which would suit our purposes   However,  4.g3  is tricky. After  4...d5   4...g6  5.Bg2  Bg7  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  O-O  8.O-O  is a well-known position. I think that Black can gradually equalize here, but it's almost universally considered to be more pleasant for White.  5.d4!   there is also  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nc7  is the Rubinstein Variation - comfortable for Black, but there's an awful lot to know.  5...cxd4  6.Nxd4  dxc4  7.Nxc6  Qxd1+  8.Nxd1  bxc6  9.Bg2  Nd5  10.Ne3  e6  11.Nxc4  Ba6  is probably ok for Black, but it is kind of dreary, and White scores over 60% here. }
4. e3
{ This has always been considered critical. White revs up for d4-d5 kicking the c6-knight. }
4... Nf6
{ Black avoids  4...Bg7  5.d4  when d4-d5 will kick the knight. This is playable but risky. }
5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 { 6.Nxd4  Bg7  reaches the Maroczy Fail chapter. } 6... d5
7. cxd5 Nxd5
{ This can also arise from the Caro-Kann: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.c4  Nf6  5.Nc3  Nc6  6.Nf3  g6  7.cxd5  Nxd5 }
8. Qb3 Nxc3
{ Here  8...Nb6?  is out of the question because  9.d5  forces the pathetic  9...Nb8  .   Black does have a solid alternative in  8...e6!?  which has also become popular recently. }
9. Bc4 Nd5
{ This is a funny retreat, but it is the most ambitious move. Trying to hold on to the piece is out of the question:  9...Ne4?  10.Bxf7+  Kd7  11.Qe6+  Kc7  12.Qxe4  regains the piece with a winning position.   Black does have a solid alternative in  9...e6  10.bxc3  Bg7   10...Bd7  and  10...Na5  are also possible.  11.Ba3  Bf8  12.Bxf8  Kxf8  13.O-O  This position favours White, but only slightly. }
10. Bxd5 e6 11. Bxc6+
{ This is played 99% of the time. White gives away the bishop but secures the d4-pawn, and splits Black's pawns as well. The alternatives do not cause Black many problems. For example  11.Bc4  Bg7  12.d5  exd5  13.Bxd5  Qe7+!?  N  14.Be3  Qb4+=+  when the b2-pawn is weak, or  11.Be4  Bg7   11...Bb4+!?  12.Be3  Qa5+!?  N   12...O-O =  13.Bd2  Qa6  14.Bd3  Qb6=+  and here the d4-pawn is weak. }
11... bxc6 12. O-O Qd5
{ Black centralizes the queen and increases his influence on the light squares.   The natural  12...Bg7?!  is not so good because after  13.Bf4  O-O  14.Qe3  White is ready to play Bf4-h6.   The immediate  12...f6!?  is also possible.  After 12... Qd5, White has many different ways to play. He can exchange queens himself, move his queen, or leave his queen and allow Black to make the exchange, although the second player is hardly obligated to do so.In general, we do not have to memorize too much here. It is more important to learn different plans and get a feel for the position. Black has to be a bit careful with his king, which will often take shelter on f7. White has to try to maintain some control of the position, as Black not only has the Bishop-pair but pawn play - with ...c5 as well as a potential advance of the kingside pawns. }
13. Qc3 { I have played this myself a few times. } 13... f6
{ The natural-looking 13…  Bg7  is not the right idea.  14.Bf4  O-O  15.Rfc1  Bb7  16.Qe3  +/= Vigorito - Movsisyan, Manchester 2015.   However,  13...Be7!?  is not a bad alternative.  14.Be3  O-O  15.Ne5  Bb7  16.f3  Rfd8  17.Rfc1  Rac8 =  Vigorito - Jimenez Corrales, Norwood 2018. }
14. Be3
{ 14.Bf4  looks more active, but Black can immediately play  14...g5  , similar to what we saw in the 13.Bf4 line. }
14... Be7
{ This is technically a novelty, but it quickly transposes to known positions.  14...Kf7  is also possible.   Instead  14...a5?!  15.Nd2  Bb4  16.Qc2  Kf7  17.Ne4  Ba6  18.Rfc1  Rhc8  19.f3!  gave White an ideal setup in Vigorito - Lenderman, Philadelphia 2013. }
15. Rfc1 Bd7
{ Black has generally gone for this, but there is something to be said for  15...Bb7!?  with veiled threats on the long diagonal.   Or even  15...Kf7  with the idea  16.Qxc6  Qxc6  17.Rxc6  Bb7  and ...Bd5, ...a5 with compensation. We also saw this idea in 13.Be3 #2 }
16. Nd2
{ This natural move has not been played in this exact position, but it transposes to a top matchup. }
16... Kf7 { Or  16...g5!? } 17. Nc4 Rhb8 18. Bf4 Rb5
{ This is a typical strategically complicated position. } 19. Rd1 Be8 20. b3
Rd8 21. Qe1 Qd7 22. Bd2 Rd5 23. Ba5 Rc8
{ The position was pretty level in So - Duda, Leon 2017. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 10: Three Knights - Panov w/Nf3 Transposition"]
[Black "13.Qc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arise after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2.e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5
{ White has three real approaches here: he can play 2. Nf3 with a quick d4; he can play 2. Nc3 and g3; finally, White can also play both knights out to keep us guessing. }
2. Nf3 Nc6
{ This will be our move order. Instead  2...Nf6  really would reduce our options.  I think 2... Nf6 is a good move if Black is aiming for a quick ...d5, which is a favorite method of Grunfeld players, or a Hedgehog setup with ...b6, a favorite of Nimzo/Queen's Indian players, in which case the c6-knight would not be well placed.   Another option is  2...g6  , but that allows White to set up a Maroczy Bind with  3.e4  Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Bg7  6.Be3  Having played both sides here, I consider this to be favorable for White. }
3. Nc3 g6
{ Instead  3...e5  would be nice to recommend, and indeed this is a favorite of one of our heroes - MVL. Now  4.g3  g6  would bring us to the Pure Symmetrical lines   However,  4.e3  is another story.  4...Nf6  and now the main line with  5.d4  cxd4  6.exd4  e4  is interesting at least   Instead White can play  5.Be2!?   or  5.a3!?  I think Black is more or less compelled to play  5...d5  with a Reversed Sicilian of sorts. If we wanted to play like that,  1...e5  would be a good start!   Unsurprisingly,  3...Nf6  is very solid. Then  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  e6  reaches the Four Knights, which would suit our purposes   However,  4.g3  is tricky. After  4...d5   4...g6  5.Bg2  Bg7  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  O-O  8.O-O  is a well-known position. I think that Black can gradually equalize here, but it's almost universally considered to be more pleasant for White.  5.d4!   there is also  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nc7  is the Rubinstein Variation - comfortable for Black, but there's an awful lot to know.  5...cxd4  6.Nxd4  dxc4  7.Nxc6  Qxd1+  8.Nxd1  bxc6  9.Bg2  Nd5  10.Ne3  e6  11.Nxc4  Ba6  is probably ok for Black, but it is kind of dreary, and White scores over 60% here. }
4. e3
{ This has always been considered critical. White revs up for d4-d5 kicking the c6-knight. }
4... Nf6
{ Black avoids  4...Bg7  5.d4  when d4-d5 will kick the knight. This is playable but risky. }
5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 { 6.Nxd4  Bg7  reaches the Maroczy Fail chapter. } 6... d5
7. cxd5 Nxd5
{ This can also arise from the Caro-Kann: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.c4  Nf6  5.Nc3  Nc6  6.Nf3  g6  7.cxd5  Nxd5 }
8. Qb3 Nxc3
{ Here  8...Nb6?  is out of the question because  9.d5  forces the pathetic  9...Nb8  .   Black does have a solid alternative in  8...e6!?  which has also become popular recently. }
9. Bc4 Nd5
{ This is a funny retreat, but it is the most ambitious move. Trying to hold on to the piece is out of the question:  9...Ne4?  10.Bxf7+  Kd7  11.Qe6+  Kc7  12.Qxe4  regains the piece with a winning position.   Black does have a solid alternative in  9...e6  10.bxc3  Bg7   10...Bd7  and  10...Na5  are also possible.  11.Ba3  Bf8  12.Bxf8  Kxf8  13.O-O  This position favours White, but only slightly. }
10. Bxd5 e6 11. Bxc6+
{ This is played 99% of the time. White gives away the bishop but secures the d4-pawn, and splits Black's pawns as well. The alternatives do not cause Black many problems. For example  11.Bc4  Bg7  12.d5  exd5  13.Bxd5  Qe7+!?  N  14.Be3  Qb4+=+  when the b2-pawn is weak, or  11.Be4  Bg7   11...Bb4+!?  12.Be3  Qa5+!?  N   12...O-O =  13.Bd2  Qa6  14.Bd3  Qb6=+  and here the d4-pawn is weak. }
11... bxc6 12. O-O Qd5
{ Black centralizes the queen and increases his influence on the light squares.   The natural  12...Bg7?!  is not so good because after  13.Bf4  O-O  14.Qe3  White is ready to play Bf4-h6.   The immediate  12...f6!?  is also possible.  After 12... Qd5, White has many different ways to play. He can exchange queens himself, move his queen, or leave his queen and allow Black to make the exchange, although the second player is hardly obligated to do so.In general, we do not have to memorize too much here. It is more important to learn different plans and get a feel for the position. Black has to be a bit careful with his king, which will often take shelter on f7. White has to try to maintain some control of the position, as Black not only has the Bishop-pair but pawn play - with ...c5 as well as a potential advance of the kingside pawns. }
13. Qc3 { I have played this myself a few times. } 13... f6
{ The natural-looking 13…  Bg7  is not the right idea.  14.Bf4  O-O  15.Rfc1  Bb7  16.Qe3  +/= Vigorito - Movsisyan, Manchester 2015.   However,  13...Be7!?  is not a bad alternative.  14.Be3  O-O  15.Ne5  Bb7  16.f3  Rfd8  17.Rfc1  Rac8 =  Vigorito - Jimenez Corrales, Norwood 2018. }
14. Be3
{ 14.Bf4  looks more active, but Black can immediately play  14...g5  , similar to what we saw in the 13.Bf4 line. }
14... Be7
{ This is technically a novelty, but it quickly transposes to known positions.  14...Kf7  is also possible.   Instead  14...a5?!  15.Nd2  Bb4  16.Qc2  Kf7  17.Ne4  Ba6  18.Rfc1  Rhc8  19.f3!  gave White an ideal setup in Vigorito - Lenderman, Philadelphia 2013. }
15. Rfc1 Bd7
{ Black has generally gone for this, but there is something to be said for  15...Bb7!?  with veiled threats on the long diagonal.   Or even  15...Kf7  with the idea  16.Qxc6  Qxc6  17.Rxc6  Bb7  and ...Bd5, ...a5 with compensation. We also saw this idea in 13.Be3 #2 }
16. Ne1
{ With ...Ba6 unavailable, White chooses this secondary route for the knight. }
16... Kf7 17. Nd3 Rab8 18. f3
{ A good example of Black's kingside possibilities can be seen after  18.Rc2  g5  19.b3  h5  when a 2700+ player had trouble figuring out how to react to Black's advance.  20.Nc5  Bc8  21.Qa5 ?!  h4  22.h3 ?  g4  23.hxg4  h3  24.f3  hxg2  25.Kxg2 ?  This was Tomashevsky - Flores, Doha 2016. Now Black missed a great opportunity with  25...e5!  -+ with the idea  ...Bxg4 }
18... Rhd8 19. b3 Be8
{ This may look funny, but the bishop is very flexible here. } 20. Rd1
{ Or  20.Nc5  Rb5 } 20... g5 21. Rac1 Kg7 22. Qe1 Bg6 { with unclear play. }
23. Nc5 Rb5 24. Bf2 Kf7 25. h3 Bf5 26. Qe2 h5 27. g4 hxg4 28. hxg4 Bg6 29. Re1
{ An instructive mistake. } 29... Bxc5
{ This is often a good idea if White is forced to recapture with the pawn. Black central pawn majority tens to mean more than White's 3:2 on the queenside. }
30. dxc5 Bd3 31. Qe3 Rb4 32. Bg3 e5
{ Black has the better bishop and the better pawn structure. } 33. Rcd1
{ White wisely bailed out with a draw offer which was accepted in Milos- Reis, Recife 2013. However... }
33... Rd4 { or  33...a5  would just be great for Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 11: Four Knights - 6.g3 Qb6 7.Nb3"]
[Black "9.Qe2 d6 10.f4 Nc6 11.Bg2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arise after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2.e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5
{ White has three real approaches here: he can play 2. Nf3 with a quick d4; he can play 2. Nc3 and g3; finally, White can also play both knights out to keep us guessing. }
2. Nf3 Nc6
{ This will be our move order. Instead  2...Nf6  really would reduce our options.  I think 2... Nf6 is a good move if Black is aiming for a quick ...d5, which is a favorite method of Grunfeld players, or a Hedgehog setup with ...b6, a favorite of Nimzo/Queen's Indian players, in which case the c6-knight would not be well placed.   Another option is  2...g6  , but that allows White to set up a Maroczy Bind with  3.e4  Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Bg7  6.Be3  Having played both sides here, I consider this to be favorable for White. }
3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ Last reminder - not  5...g6  6.e4  with a Maroczy!  After 5... e6 we reach our starting point for the Four Knights variation. This setup has always been considered to be very healthy for Black. In fact, a couple of popular white repertoire books have deliberately set out to avoid this position. One of our heroes will be the French super-GM Maxime Vachier-Lagrave  (MVL)  who plays this setup very often against all comers.  There is quite a bit to know here, so despite its good reputation, this setup has been largely ignored from Black's point of view in chess literature for a long time. }
6. g3 { This typical 'English' move has traditionally been the main line. }
6... Qb6
{ This direct attack aims to throw White off balance. The d4-knight is attacked, but often Black will play ...Ne5, hitting the c4-pawn, and also creating the possibility of ...Qc6.  The ensuing play can be quite varied and there is quite a bit of theory here. A lot of the positions are fun and Black has his share of the chances. We will see a lot of ideas repeated for both sides. It is not uncommon for White to offer up the c4-pawn for an initiative, so do not sell your soul to win this pawn.   The knight moves ...Ne5 and ...Nfg4 are typical for Black, as is the counterstrike ...g5 in certain positions with a white bishop on f4. }
7. Nb3
{ The knight is secure here, and it also supports a potential c4-c5 advance. Black should always watch for this move, even if it's a pawn sacrifice. }
7... Ne5 { This does not only attack the c4-pawn, but it sets up ...Qc6. } 8.
e4 Bb4 { Black develops quickly and puts pressure on the e4-pawn. } 9. Qe2
{ This is the main line. White protects the e4-pawn, and also covers the c4-pawn to prepare Bg2.   9.Be3  would be premature. The typical  9...Qc6!  attacks both the  e4- and c4-pawns. }
9... d6
{ Bringing some protection to the dark squares. Black has to time ...Bxc3 carefully, because if the capture is done too early White will be able to play Ba3 and the bishop will slice through Black's position. Now White chooses between immediate aggression in the center or the prevention of doubled pawns. }
10. f4 { This is the older line. } 10... Nc6
{ Simply retreating is best.   10...Bxc3+?  11.bxc3  Nc6  12.Ba3!  is something to avoid. }
11. Bg2 { This is natural, but this not a very good move order for White. }
11... e5
{ This is a thematic idea. Black sometimes threatens ...Bg4, and this move also increases Black's dark-squared control - especially important is the d4-square. }
12. Bd2
{ Other moves are even worse:  12.Be3?  Nd4!  13.Qd3  Nc2+  =/+   Or  12.f5  Bd7!?  =/+ }
12... O-O { White is already left fighting for survival. } 13. O-O-O Bg4
{ 13...a5  is also good. } 14. Bf3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Qa6 *

