{ This will be our move order. Instead  2...Nf6  really would reduce our options.  I think 2... Nf6 is a good move if Black is aiming for a quick ...d5, which is a favorite method of Grunfeld players, or a Hedgehog setup with ...b6, a favorite of Nimzo/Queen's Indian players, in which case the c6-knight would not be well placed.   Another option is  2...g6  , but that allows White to set up a Maroczy Bind with  3.e4  Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Bg7  6.Be3  Having played both sides here, I consider this to be favorable for White. }
3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ We avoid  4...g6  which allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ Last reminder - not  5...g6  6.e4  with a Maroczy!  After 5... e6 we reach our starting point for the Four Knights variation. This setup has always been considered to be very healthy for Black. In fact, a couple of popular white repertoire books have deliberately set out to avoid this position. One of our heroes will be the French super-GM Maxime Vachier-Lagrave  (MVL)  who plays this setup very often against all comers.  There is quite a bit to know here, so despite its good reputation, this setup has been largely ignored from Black's point of view in chess literature for a long time. }
6. g3 { This typical 'English' move has traditionally been the main line. }
6... Qb6
{ This direct attack aims to throw White off balance. The d4-knight is attacked, but often Black will play ...Ne5, hitting the c4-pawn, and also creating the possibility of ...Qc6.  The ensuing play can be quite varied and there is quite a bit of theory here. A lot of the positions are fun and Black has his share of the chances. We will see a lot of ideas repeated for both sides. It is not uncommon for White to offer up the c4-pawn for an initiative, so do not sell your soul to win this pawn.   The knight moves ...Ne5 and ...Nfg4 are typical for Black, as is the counterstrike ...g5 in certain positions with a white bishop on f4. }
7. Nb3
{ The knight is secure here, and it also supports a potential c4-c5 advance. Black should always watch for this move, even if it's a pawn sacrifice. }
7... Ne5 { This does not only attack the c4-pawn, but it sets up ...Qc6. } 8.
e4 Bb4 { Black develops quickly and puts pressure on the e4-pawn. } 9. Qe2
{ This is the main line. White protects the e4-pawn, and also covers the c4-pawn to prepare Bg2.   9.Be3  would be premature. The typical  9...Qc6!  attacks both the  e4- and c4-pawns. }
9... d6
{ Bringing some protection to the dark squares. Black has to time ...Bxc3 carefully, because if the capture is done too early White will be able to play Ba3 and the bishop will slice through Black's position. Now White chooses between immediate aggression in the center or the prevention of doubled pawns. }
10. f4 { This is the older line. } 10... Nc6
{ Simply retreating is best.   10...Bxc3+?  11.bxc3  Nc6  12.Ba3!  is something to avoid. }
11. Be3
{ With this move White prepares castling kingside. Other moves leave the g1-a7 diagonal open, and after so many pawn advances White's king can easily become exposed. }
11... Bxc3+ { Now that there is no Ba3, it's time to smash the pawns. } 12.
bxc3 Qc7 13. Bg2 e5
{ Blocking e4-e5 and taking a stand on the dark-squares.   13...b6?!  14.e5!  causes problems.   The older  13...O-O  is quite playable though. If allowed, Black will follow up with ...b6 to prevent c4-c5. Then ...Be6 or ...Ba6 will lay siege to the c4-pawn. }
14. c5 b6
{ This is still a good move. Black eliminates the cramping effect of the c5-pawn to gain some space for his pieces. }
15. cxd6 Qxd6 16. O-O O-O 17. Rfd1 Qe7
{ Here  17...Qa3?!  runs into  18.Qb5!  Bb7  19.Bc5!  After  19...bxc5  20.Qxb7  Rac8  21.Bh3!  and White is winning. }
18. f5 Qa3
{ Other moves like 18... h6 or simply 18... Bb7 were also possible. } 19. Bc1
Qa4 20. Bg5 Ba6 21. Qe3 Rfd8 { Black can allow the doubled pawns. } 22. Bxf6
gxf6 { White decides to bail out, else he will end up worse. } 23. Qh6 Rxd1+
24. Rxd1 Qxa2 25. Qxf6 Qxb3
{ And White gave perpetual check in Svane - Ragger, Trier 2016. } *

