{ This direct attack aims to throw White off balance. The d4-knight is attacked, but often Black will play ...Ne5, hitting the c4-pawn, and also creating the possibility of ...Qc6.  The ensuing play can be quite varied and there is quite a bit of theory here. A lot of the positions are fun and Black has his share of the chances. We will see a lot of ideas repeated for both sides. It is not uncommon for White to offer up the c4-pawn for an initiative, so do not sell your soul to win this pawn.   The knight moves ...Ne5 and ...Nfg4 are typical for Black, as is the counterstrike ...g5 in certain positions with a white bishop on f4. }
