{ The knight is secure here, and it also supports a potential c4-c5 advance. Black should always watch for this move, even if it's a pawn sacrifice. }
7... Ne5 { This does not only attack the c4-pawn, but it sets up ...Qc6. } 8.
e4 Bb4 { Black develops quickly and puts pressure on the e4-pawn. } 9. c5
{ This pawn sacrifice from the home laboratory of Alexander Morozevich was first played against Veselin Topalov, who had clearly checked it at home. }
9... Qc6
{ An excellent response. Instead  9...Bxc5  is possible, but after  10.Nxc5  Qxc5  11.Be2!  with the idea  f4 and Be3, White is getting quite a bit of play.  Topalov's move is more disruptive, and the c4-pawn may still get eaten later. }
10. f3 { I suppose White could repeat with  10.Bg2  Qb5  11.Bf1  Qc6 } 10... b6
{ Black fights for the initiative rather than seeking material gains. Do not be tempted by  10...Nxe4  11.fxe4  Qxe4+  12.Qe2  Qxh1  13.Qxe5  . White's minor pieces are in play while the black rooks will not show their force for a long time to come. }
11. cxb6 Nxe4
{ Now this gains in force, although accelerating development with  10...O-O!?  could be even stronger. }
12. fxe4 Qxe4+ 13. Qe2 Qxh1 14. Qxe5 Ba6
{ This brings immediate pressure. Black's a8-rook is also poised to enter the game. }
