Bg2
{ White is willing to just give up the pawn for a couple of tempi. This is another one of Dubov's pet lines. }
8... Nxc4 9. O-O d6
{ Black has done quite well with this move. Instead  9...d5?!  looks very sensible, but White can open the position with  10.e4  and Black is really not ready for that.   The most common move is  9...Be7  when  10.e4  d6  looks similar, but now  11.Qe2  hits our knight immediately. After  11...Qa6   11...Ne5  12.Be3  Qd8  12.h3  was seen in one of Dubov's blitz games: White is ready to kick back the knight with  f4 followed by centralizing the rooks  12.Nd2  Nxd2  13.Qxa6  bxa6  14.Bxd2  Rb8  15.b3  O-O=  Black should be fine. White has some compensation, but not enough for an advantage.  With 9... d6 we give ourselves more options. }
10. Qd4 Qxd4 11. Nxd4 a6 { This guards the b5-square. } *

