12. e4 { Instead  12.Bg5  Nd7!  transposes to 11. Bg5. } 12... d4
{ Also possible is  12...Qa5!?  when it's not easy for White to avoid a repetition:  13.Qd3   Black consolidates after  13.Qd4?  e5  14.Qd3  d4  -/+  13...Ne5  14.Qe3   Worse is  14.Qd4  Nc6  -/+  14...Nc4  15.Qd3  Ne5=  with a repetition. }
13. e5
{ This is untried but looks the most consistent. It's hard to imagine any white players getting here, especially when Black has equalizing alternatives on moves 11 and 12 along the way. }
13... Nxe5 14. Na4 Qd6
{ Usually  14...Qa7?!  can be played, but not here because of  15.Bb2  Nc6  16.Bxc6+  bxc6  17.Bxd4  +/- }
15. Bb2
{ White can win back the pawn, but the simplifications will lead to equality. }
15... Bd7
{ Forcing clear equality.  15...Nc6!?  16.Nb6  Rb8  17.Nc4  Qc7  18.Bxc6+  Qxc6  19.Qxd4  O-O  also looks ok for Black. }
16. Qxd4 Qxd4 17. Bxd4 Bxa4 18. Bxe5 Bc6
{ This is the safest. Black trades off one of White's bishops. } 19. Bxc6+ bxc6
20. Rac1 Rc8 21. Rc4 Ke7 22. Rfc1 Rhd8 23. Rxc6 Rd1+
{ This makes life easier by taking pressure off of the a6-pawn. } 24. Rxd1 Rxc6
{ This is equal, but I would play on with Black. } *

