{ 9...Qc6?  looks good, but  10.h3!  Nf3   10...Qxh1  11.hxg4  threatens both 12. Bxe5 and 12. Nc7+, and  11...Nf3  12.Ke2  +- does not help.   10...g5  is a typical idea, but  11.Bxg5  Nf3+  12.Qxf3!  Qxf3  13.Nc7#  is mate!  11.Ke2  Nge5  12.b3  leaves Black in a tangle.  12...g5  13.Bg2!  Greenfeld fell into this vs Korchnoi, then used it himself the following year.  13...gxf4  14.exf4±  will win back the pieces with advantage. We should always check White's 'blunders' where Black can take on  h1  or  f2  - it could backfire! }
10. h3 { This leads to an equal endgame... usually. } 10... axb5 11. hxg4 Nxc4
12. Rc1 { This was Giri's recent try. The play is rather forced. } 12... d5 13.
b3 Bb4 { A good reaction. Black will win back the piece. } 14. bxc4 Ra3 15. Be5
f6 16. Bd4 Qa5 17. Be2 Bxc3+ 18. Rxc3
{ This was White's idea. Instead  18.Bxc3?  Rxc3  19.Rxc3  Qxc3  20.Kf1  bxc4  -+ just leaves White down two pawns. }
18... Rxc3 19. Kf1
{ Giri was moving very quickly here. It was an interesting idea to check this because the computer likes Black for quite a while, meaning black players probably did not pay much attention to it. }
19... b4
{ After this Giri went into the think tank.  19...bxc4  was certainly the focus of his preparation.  20.g5  O-O  21.Kg2!  fxg5   21...e5?  22.Bxc3  Qxc3  23.Qxd5+  actually leads to mate.  22.Qb1  Rd3  23.Bxd3  cxd3  24.Qxd3  gives White a nice initiative. }
20. g5
{ White is trying to get the initiative, just like in the previous note.  20.Bxc3?  bxc3  -/+ is not in White's interest. }
20... e5 21. Bxc3 bxc3 22. gxf6 gxf6
{ This was Giri - Nepomniachtchi, Yekaterinburg 2020. Black is ok and even went on to win. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 13: Four Knights - 6.g3 Qb6 7.Ndb5 Ne5 8.Bf4"]
[Black "9.e3 a6 10.h3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arise after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2.e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5
{ White has three real approaches here: he can play 2. Nf3 with a quick d4; he can play 2. Nc3 and g3; finally, White can also play both knights out to keep us guessing. }
2. Nf3 Nc6
{ This will be our move order. Instead  2...Nf6  really would reduce our options.  I think 2... Nf6 is a good move if Black is aiming for a quick ...d5, which is a favorite method of Grunfeld players, or a Hedgehog setup with ...b6, a favorite of Nimzo/Queen's Indian players, in which case the c6-knight would not be well placed.   Another option is  2...g6  , but that allows White to set up a Maroczy Bind with  3.e4  Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Bg7  6.Be3  Having played both sides here, I consider this to be favorable for White. }
3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ Again,  4...g6  allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ Last reminder - not  5...g6  6.e4  with a Maroczy!  After 5... e6 we reach our starting point for the Four Knights variation. This setup has always been considered to be very healthy for Black. In fact, a couple of popular white repertoire books have deliberately set out to avoid this position. One of our heroes will be the French super-GM Maxime Vachier-Lagrave @@StartBracket@@MVL@@EndBracket@@ who plays this setup very often against all comers. }
6. g3 { This typical 'English' move has traditionally been the main line. }
6... Qb6
{ This direct attack aims to throw White off balance. The d4-knight is attacked, but often Black will play ...Ne5, hitting the c4-pawn, and also creating the possibility of ...Qc6.  The ensuing play can be quite varied and there is quite a bit of theory here. A lot of the positions are fun and Black has his share of the chances. We will see a lot of ideas repeated for both sides. It is not uncommon for White to offer up the c4-pawn for an initiative, so do not sell your soul to win this pawn.   The knight moves ...Ne5 and ...Nfg4 are typical for Black, as is the counterstrike ...g5 in certain positions with a white bishop on f4. }
7. Ndb5
{ This is White's most aggressive option. The knight is a bit out on a limb, but we will see that White has a variety of tactical ideas. Typical ideas are Bf4, taking aim at the c7-square, Qa4, and Black always has to watch out for c4-c5. The lines can be varied and complicated, but Black is in good shape theoretically. }
7... Ne5
{ Just as it did against 7. Nb3, this attacks the c4-pawn and creates the possibility of ...Qc6. }
8. Bf4
{ This is the most forcing continuation. The knight cannot move because of Nc7+. }
8... Nfg4
{ This defends the e5-knight and attacks the f2-pawn. Instead  8...d6!?  is too passive. After  9.Bg2  Black cannot play  9...Nxc4 ??  because of  10.Qa4  +- }
9. e3
{ An obvious move, but we will see that White does not always have to prevent something from landing on the f2-square! After playing both e3 and g3, White must always watch out for ...g5 or ...e5 which could trap his bishop.   9.Qd4 ?!  would only be suitable for blitz.  9...Bc5  10.Bxe5  Bxd4  11.Bxd4  Qc6  -/+ }
9... a6
{ 9...Qc6?  looks good, but  10.h3!  Nf3   10...Qxh1  11.hxg4  threatens both 12. Bxe5 and 12. Nc7+, and  11...Nf3  12.Ke2  +- does not help.   10...g5  is a typical idea, but  11.Bxg5  Nf3+  12.Qxf3!  Qxf3  13.Nc7#  is mate!  11.Ke2  Nge5  12.b3  leaves Black in a tangle.  12...g5  13.Bg2!  Greenfeld fell into this vs Korchnoi, then used it himself the following year.  13...gxf4  14.exf4±  will win back the pieces with advantage. We should always check White's 'blunders' where Black can take on  h1  or  f2  - it could backfire! }
10. h3 { This leads to an equal endgame... usually. } 10... axb5 11. hxg4 Nxc4
12. Qb3 { This is the usual move. White wins his pawn back. } 12... d5 13. Bxc4
{ This is universally played. After  13.Qxb5+  Qxb5  14.Nxb5  Bb4+  15.Kd1  Ke7  when Black is better.   13.Nxb5  Qa5+!  14.Nc3  Bb4  is also quite comfortable for Black. }
13... dxc4 14. Qxb5+ Qxb5 15. Nxb5 Ra5
{ This is less common than the alternative  15...Bb4+  but it looks cleaner to me. }
16. Rh5 { An awkward looking move. } 16... Bb4+ 17. Ke2 f6 18. Nd6+ Bxd6 19.
Bxd6 e5
{ This is even more pleasant for Black - White's pieces are misplaced. } *

