Bxe5 { 12.Nxa8?  gxf4  -+ } 12... Qe3+
{ Even here Black has a backup option with  12...Nxe5  13.Nxa8  b5! } 13. Kc2
Qxe5 14. Nxa8 Ne3+ 15. Kb3 Bc5
{ Black seems to be doing rather well here. He has more pieces in play and dominates in the center. Of course the a8-knight is in some trouble too. Black would like to play ... Ke7, ...d5, ...Bd7, and then ...Rxa8. That's a lot of moves to make, but it's not clear what White can do! }
16. a3 { Making an escape for the king. } 16... Ke7 17. Ka2 d5 18. Qa5
{ White is trying to extricate his knight. } 18... dxc4 19. Bh3
{ This connects the rooks. The immediate escape attempts run into problems. }
19... Bd7 20. Rhd1
{ The best try. Now both sides must head down the rabbit hole, but it is Black who has the draw in hand. }
20... Rxa8
{ This allows Black to keep pressing. Instead the more obvious  20...Nxd1  21.Rxd1  Rxa8  allows White to hold with  22.Nd5+  exd5  23.Qxc5+  Qd6  24.Qxd6+  Kxd6  25.Bxd7  Kxd7  26.Rxd5+ }
21. Nd5+ exd5 22. Qxc5+ Kd8 23. Bxd7 Kxd7
{ Compared to the line above, Black remains down the exchange, but he has two pawns and controls most of the board. }
24. Qb5+ Ke6
{ There is also  24...Kc7  25.Qc5+  Kd7  repeating moves, but Black should play on. }
25. Qxb7 Rb8 26. Qa6+ Qd6
{ Another possibility is  26...Rb6  27.Qc8+  Kf6  28.Rd2  Kg7  with unclear play. In a correspondence game, perhaps it's just a draw. }
27. Qxa7 Nxd1 28. Rxd1 Qb6 29. Qxb6+ Rxb6
{ All of this occurred in Walters - Miettinen, correspondence 2017. Black is the one pressing, but it seems that with perfect play White can hold. This is still more challenging to White than the forced draw that can result after 9... g5 10. Bxe5 Qxf2+! }
