{ Now Black is hoping to play ...d5 when White does not have his Hedgehog, but Black does have his development lead. }
8. Nf3
{ This is the main move. White prevents ...d5 and keeps his knight on an active square where it helps control the center. }
8... Qc7
{ This prevents Bf4 and is Black's main response.   Black could also play  8...b6  9.Bf4  Bb7  10.Be2  Rc8  11.O-O  d6  .   A more topical move is  8...Qa5!?  with the idea   9.Bd2  Qh5  10.Be2  d5  This eventually equalized in a Carlsen - Anand game, amongst others.   However,  9.Bd3  d5  10.cxd5  exd5  11.exd5  Nxd5  12.Bxh7+  Kxh7  13.Qxd5  asks more questions. It all looks a bit dreary for Black to me. }
9. Be2 { The main move. } 9... b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. Bg5
{ This non-pin is White's most popular move. Instead  11.Be3?!  would run into  11...Ng4   and  11.h3  could be met with  11...Ne5 }
11... Ne5
{ This direct move is a favorite of MVL. Instead  11...h6  is more popular, but considering the bishop usually retreats to  h4  anyway, why should we bother? A bunch of rook moves are also playable:  11...Rac8  ,  11...Rfd8  , and  11...Rad8  for example. }
12. Bh4 d6
{ Black intends ...Ng6 when Bg3 would drop the e4-pawn. Black may also follow up with ...Nh5 to snare White's dark-squared bishop. }
13. Nxe5 dxe5
{ This gives a typical unclear position. Black's doubled pawns give him good central control, and it's not so easy for White to utilize his queenside pawn majority. }
