8... Qc7
{ This prevents Bf4 and is Black's main response.   Black could also play  8...b6  9.Bf4  Bb7  10.Be2  Rc8  11.O-O  d6  .   A more topical move is  8...Qa5!?  with the idea   9.Bd2  Qh5  10.Be2  d5  This eventually equalized in a Carlsen - Anand game, amongst others.   However,  9.Bd3  d5  10.cxd5  exd5  11.exd5  Nxd5  12.Bxh7+  Kxh7  13.Qxd5  asks more questions. It all looks a bit dreary for Black to me. }
9. Be2 { The main move. } 9... b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. Bg5
{ This non-pin is White's most popular move. Instead  11.Be3?!  would run into  11...Ng4   and  11.h3  could be met with  11...Ne5 }
11... Ne5
{ This direct move is a favorite of MVL. Instead  11...h6  is more popular, but considering the bishop usually retreats to  h4  anyway, why should we bother? A bunch of rook moves are also playable:  11...Rac8  ,  11...Rfd8  , and  11...Rad8  for example. }
12. Nxe5 Qxe5 { Hitting the g5-bishop as well as the e4-pawn. } 13. f4 Qc5+ 14.
Kh1 Nxe4 { Although White can win it back as follows: } 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. b4
Qd6 17. Qxd6 Bxd6 18. Rad1 Bc7 19. Rxd7 Rac8 { With an equal position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 15: Four Knights - 6.a3"]
[Black "7.e4 O-O 8.Nf3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arise after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2.e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5
{ White has three real approaches here: he can play 2. Nf3 with a quick d4; he can play 2. Nc3 and g3; finally, White can also play both knights out to keep us guessing. }
2. Nf3 Nc6
{ This will be our move order. Instead  2...Nf6  really would reduce our options.  I think 2... Nf6 is a good move if Black is aiming for a quick ...d5, which is a favorite method of Grunfeld players, or a Hedgehog setup with ...b6, a favorite of Nimzo/Queen's Indian players, in which case the c6-knight would not be well placed.   Another option is  2...g6  , but that allows White to set up a Maroczy Bind with  3.e4  Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Bg7  6.Be3  Having played both sides here, I consider this to be favorable for White. }
3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ Again,  4...g6  allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ Last reminder - not  5...g6  6.e4  with a Maroczy!  After 5... e6 we reach our starting point for the Four Knights variation. This setup has always been considered to be very healthy for Black. In fact, a couple of popular white repertoire books have deliberately set out to avoid this position. One of our heroes will be the French super-GM Maxime Vachier-Lagrave @@StartBracket@@MVL@@EndBracket@@ who plays this setup very often against all comers. }
6. a3
{ This little prophylactic move is second in popularity, with almost as many games played as  6.g3  . White takes a move to prevent  ...Bb4  while maintaining maximum flexibility. While  6.g3  presents more of a memory challenge,  6.a3  makes it more difficult for Black to create active counterplay. }
6... Be7
{ Instead  6...d5  7.cxd5  exd5  allows White to develop his bishop actively with  8.Bg5  or  8.Bf4  to battle the IQP.   Another way of playing is  6...Bc5  7.Nb3  Be7  which would be similar to our main line, but with the knight on b3 instead of d4; this would seem to help us, but White will play  8.e4  and he now has more control of the d-file.   A similar issue arises after  6...Qb6  7.Nb3  Be7  . Again, White plays  8.e4  and here Black will lose time with the queen rather than the bishop.   A popular modern method is to play  6...Bc5  7.Nb3  Bb6!?  intending  ...d5  . After  8.c5!?  Bc7  9.g3  the jury is still out, but overall White has kept a good score.  With the text move we simply continue our development and wait to see what White is up to. }
7. e4
{ This is the most popular move. White wants to play a Hedgehog, even though he has already spent a move on a3. I am not a big Hedgehog player, but I know that usually Black does not put a knight on c6 - ...Nbd7 would be more typical. Because of these two factors I believe Black should play rather directly, because ...Nc6 is a developing move while a3 was not! }
7... O-O
{ Now Black is hoping to play ...d5 when White does not have his Hedgehog, but Black does have his development lead. }
8. Nf3
{ This is the main move. White prevents ...d5 and keeps his knight on an active square where it helps control the center. }
8... Qc7
{ This prevents Bf4 and is Black's main response.   Black could also play  8...b6  9.Bf4  Bb7  10.Be2  Rc8  11.O-O  d6  .   A more topical move is  8...Qa5!?  with the idea   9.Bd2  Qh5  10.Be2  d5  This eventually equalized in a Carlsen - Anand game, amongst others.   However,  9.Bd3  d5  10.cxd5  exd5  11.exd5  Nxd5  12.Bxh7+  Kxh7  13.Qxd5  asks more questions. It all looks a bit dreary for Black to me. }
9. Be2 { The main move. } 9... b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. Bg5
{ This non-pin is White's most popular move. Instead  11.Be3?!  would run into  11...Ng4   and  11.h3  could be met with  11...Ne5 }
11... Ne5
{ This direct move is a favorite of MVL. Instead  11...h6  is more popular, but considering the bishop usually retreats to  h4  anyway, why should we bother? A bunch of rook moves are also playable:  11...Rac8  ,  11...Rfd8  , and  11...Rad8  for example. }
12. Nxe5 Qxe5 { Hitting the g5-bishop as well as the e4-pawn. } 13. Bh4 Rac8
{ Black has also tried  13...Rfd8  as well as  13...Bxe4!?  which, rather than winning a pawn, loses an exchange after  14.Bxf6  Bxf6  15.Nxe4  Qxe4  16.Bf3  , although Black gets a second pawn after  16...Qxc4  . Black has done well here, but I think White is better after  17.Rc1   17.Bxa8  Rxa8  18.Rc1  Qd4  transposes.  17...Qd4  18.Bxa8  Rxa8  19.Rc7!  Now, however, the e4-pawn really is hanging. }
14. f3 { This falls into a little trap: } 14... Ng4 *

