{ Black intends ...Rfd8 or ...Bc6 next. If White grabs the pawn with } 17. Qxd7
Bc6 18. Qd1 { This is a better try, but Black is doing well after } 18... Rfd8
19. Qe1 Bc5 { when ...Bd4 will likely come next. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 16: Four Knights - 6.Ndb5 d5 7.cxd5 'pawn grab'"]
[Black "9.Qxd5 Bb4+ 10.Bd2 Qe7 11.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arise after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2.e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5
{ White has three real approaches here: he can play 2. Nf3 with a quick d4; he can play 2. Nc3 and g3; finally, White can also play both knights out to keep us guessing. }
2. Nf3 Nc6
{ This will be our move order. Instead  2...Nf6  really would reduce our options.  I think 2... Nf6 is a good move if Black is aiming for a quick ...d5, which is a favorite method of Grunfeld players, or a Hedgehog setup with ...b6, a favorite of Nimzo/Queen's Indian players, in which case the c6-knight would not be well placed.   Another option is  2...g6  , but that allows White to set up a Maroczy Bind with  3.e4  Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Bg7  6.Be3  Having played both sides here, I consider this to be favorable for White. }
3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ Again,  4...g6  allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ Last reminder - not  5...g6  6.e4  with a Maroczy!  After 5... e6 we reach our starting point for the Four Knights variation. This setup has always been considered to be very healthy for Black. In fact, a couple of popular white repertoire books have deliberately set out to avoid this position. One of our heroes will be the French super-GM Maxime Vachier-Lagrave @@StartBracket@@MVL@@EndBracket@@ who plays this setup very often against all comers. }
6. Ndb5
{ This is an important move. White takes aim at the d6- and c7-squares. } 6...
d5
{ After  6...d6  7.Bf4  forces  7...e5  , and then  8.Bg5  gives White secure control of the  d5-square and a pleasant advantage. }
7. cxd5
{ White spots the possibility of using an old trap to win a pawn. It's a principled approach, but grabbing the pawn is time consuming. }
7... Nxd5 { Not  7...exd5??  8.Bf4  +- } 8. Nxd5
{ Instead  8.e4  Nxc3  9.Qxd8  Kxd8  10.Nxc3  Bc5  is totally fine for Black. }
8... exd5 9. Qxd5
{ Having said 'A'...   Objectively this is not too bad, but Black's position is much easier to play and in practice White's score has been downright abysmal. White could bail out with  9.e3  , but after  9...a6  10.Nd4  Bc5  or  10...Bd6  Black is totally fine.   Note that  9.Bf4??  loses to  9...Qa5  10.Nc3  d4  . }
9... Bb4+ { Of course  9...Qxd5?  10.Nc7+  was White's point. } 10. Bd2 Qe7
{ This is the most ambitious. We will castle next and play ... Rd8 or ...Be6 depending on what White does.   Black also has compensation after  10...Be6  11.Qxd8+  Rxd8   or  10...O-O!?  11.Qxd8  Rxd8  in the endgame. }
11. e3 { This is very natural, but White will quickly get into trouble. } 11...
O-O 12. a3 Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 Rd8
{ With ...Bf5, ...Nd4, ... Rac8 coming, White is in big trouble. } 14. Qc2
{ This is not possible because of: } 14... a6 15. Nc3 Nd4 { and ...Bf5. } *

