{ Having said 'A'...   Objectively this is not too bad, but Black's position is much easier to play and in practice White's score has been downright abysmal. White could bail out with  9.e3  , but after  9...a6  10.Nd4  Bc5  or  10...Bd6  Black is totally fine.   Note that  9.Bf4??  loses to  9...Qa5  10.Nc3  d4  . }
9... Bb4+ { Of course  9...Qxd5?  10.Nc7+  was White's point. } 10. Bd2 Qe7
{ This is the most ambitious. We will castle next and play ... Rd8 or ...Be6 depending on what White does.   Black also has compensation after  10...Be6  11.Qxd8+  Rxd8   or  10...O-O!?  11.Qxd8  Rxd8  in the endgame. }
11. O-O-O
{ This looks a bit crazy, but it is one of White's better tries. We saw that it is hard for White to castle kingside, and the king is hardly guaranteed safety on e1. }
11... Be6
{ Instead  11...O-O  allows the annoying  12.Bg5!  while  11...Bxd2+  12.Rxd2  O-O  could be met with  13.Qd6! }
12. Bxb4 Nxb4 13. Nd6+
{ Now Black is the one who will not get to castle! Everything is ok though. }
13... Kf8 14. Qxb7 { This allows a terrible attack even with the queens off. }
14... Qxb7 15. Nxb7 Rc8+ 16. Kd2 Rc7
{ A multi-functional move: attacking the knight but also getting ready to go to the d-file and go after White's king. }
17. Nd6 Rd7 18. Kc1 Nxa2+ 19. Kc2 Nb4+ 20. Kc1 Rc7+ 21. Kb1 Ba2+
{ wins for Black after } 22. Ka1 Bb3 { and the rook has nowhere to go: } 23.
Rb1 Nc2# *

