{ After  6...d6  7.Bf4  forces  7...e5  , and then  8.Bg5  secures control of the d5-square and gives White a pleasant advantage. }
7. Bf4
{ This is more critical than greedy pawn grabbing with  7.cxd5  which was examined in the previous chapter.  There's a little threat with Nc7+, so Black's reply is forced. }
7... e5 8. cxd5 exf4 9. dxc6 bxc6
{ We cannot trade queens ourselves because Nc7+ would still hang over our head. So we have to allow our king to be displaced. }
10. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is an important position. Black's king is a little bit exposed and his pawn structure is broken. However, he has the bishop pair and open lines for his rooks. The position is dynamically equal, and Black has decent chances of taking over the initiative. }
11. O-O-O+
{ This is very natural. White gets the rook to the d-file with tempo, secures his king, and protects the b2-pawn - all in one move. But there is a downside - the f2-pawn is a glaring weakness. }
11... Ke7
{ This modern move was likely rejected for a long time because of its clumsy appearance. However, the king is quite safe here, and ...g6 will soon take care of the f8-bishop. Black has scored very well here, and engines are already favoring Black.   The main line is  11...Bd7  , when  12.Nd6  can be met with the traditional  12...Bxd6  13.Rxd6  Ng4  or even with  12...Kc7  13.Nxf7  Ng4!?  This really highlights the weakness of  f2 - Black can give up a whole rook to take the pawn. }
12. Nd4 Bd7 { Already the position is trending towards a black advantage. } 13.
Nc2 { This is passive. } 13... g6 14. e4 Ng4 15. Rd2 Bh6 16. h3 Ne5 17. f3 Rhd8
{ Black has the bishop pair and a great outpost on e5. } *

