10. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is an important position. Black's king is a little bit exposed and his pawn structure is broken. However, he has the bishop pair and open lines for his rooks. The position is dynamically equal, and Black has decent chances of taking over the initiative. }
11. Rd1+
{ This is the most common choice. White activates the rook, but keeps the f2-pawn guarded. Black has more than one way to equalize. }
11... Bd7
{ Here  11...Ke7  is not as good. After  12.Nd4  Bd7  13.g3  we do not have ...Ng4 with such effect because the f2-pawn is covered, so Black lacks counterplay. }
12. Nd6 Kc7
{ I like this active pawn sacrifice, which maintains the bishop pair. Instead  12...Bxd6  13.Rxd6  Rb8  is the main line. White can secure the b-pawn with  14.b3  or  14.Rd2  and aspire for a tiny advantage. }
13. Nxf7 Rg8
{ Now White can either extract his knight or get going with his kingside development. }
14. Ne5 { This is the main line. The knight heads home. } 14... Rb8
{ Black has to play for activity! } 15. Nxd7
{ This eliminates Black's bishop pair and avoids losing more time with the e5-knight. }
15... Nxd7 16. g3
{ White looks to catch up in development rather than worrying about the b2-pawn. }
16... Rxb2 17. Bh3
{ The best try. White gains time by attacking the d7-knight. } 17... Nf6
{ Black has also tried  17...Nc5  18.O-O  Bd6  which is fine, but I prefer to keep the  a3-f8 diagonal open for our bishop. }
18. O-O { There is still no time for  18.gxf4  Bb4  -+ } 18... Bb4 19. Rc1 Rd8
{ Planning to come into d2. } 20. Bg2
{ White looks for counterplay against the c6-pawn. } 20... Rdd2
{ Still delaying the exchange on g3!   If  20...fxg3  21.hxg3  Rdd2  White has  22.Nd1!?  Rbc2  23.Ne3  with the better pawn structure. }
21. a3 Bxc3 22. Rxc3 Rdc2 { This move sets a little trap. } 23. Rxc2
{ Safest. } 23... Rxc2 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 17: Four Knights - 6.Ndb5 d5 7.Bf4 endgame"]
[Black "11.Rd1 #22"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arise after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2.e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5
{ White has three real approaches here: he can play 2. Nf3 with a quick d4; he can play 2. Nc3 and g3; finally, White can also play both knights out to keep us guessing. }
2. Nf3 Nc6
{ This will be our move order. Instead  2...Nf6  really would reduce our options.  I think 2... Nf6 is a good move if Black is aiming for a quick ...d5, which is a favorite method of Grunfeld players, or a Hedgehog setup with ...b6, a favorite of Nimzo/Queen's Indian players, in which case the c6-knight would not be well placed.   Another option is  2...g6  , but that allows White to set up a Maroczy Bind with  3.e4  Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Bg7  6.Be3  Having played both sides here, I consider this to be favorable for White. }
3. d4 { The direct approach. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ Again,  4...g6  allows  5.e4  with a Maroczy Bind. } 5. Nc3 e6
{ Last reminder - not  5...g6  6.e4  with a Maroczy!  After 5... e6 we reach our starting point for the Four Knights variation. This setup has always been considered to be very healthy for Black. In fact, a couple of popular white repertoire books have deliberately set out to avoid this position. One of our heroes will be the French super-GM Maxime Vachier-Lagrave @@StartBracket@@MVL@@EndBracket@@ who plays this setup very often against all comers. }
6. Ndb5
{ This is an important move. White takes aim at the d6- and c7-squares. } 6...
d5
{ After  6...d6  7.Bf4  forces  7...e5  , and then  8.Bg5  secures control of the d5-square and gives White a pleasant advantage. }
7. Bf4
{ This is more critical than greedy pawn grabbing with  7.cxd5  which was examined in the previous chapter.  There's a little threat with Nc7+, so Black's reply is forced. }
7... e5 8. cxd5 exf4 9. dxc6 bxc6
{ We cannot trade queens ourselves because Nc7+ would still hang over our head. So we have to allow our king to be displaced. }
10. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is an important position. Black's king is a little bit exposed and his pawn structure is broken. However, he has the bishop pair and open lines for his rooks. The position is dynamically equal, and Black has decent chances of taking over the initiative. }
11. Rd1+
{ This is the most common choice. White activates the rook, but keeps the f2-pawn guarded. Black has more than one way to equalize. }
11... Bd7
{ Here  11...Ke7  is not as good. After  12.Nd4  Bd7  13.g3  we do not have ...Ng4 with such effect because the f2-pawn is covered, so Black lacks counterplay. }
12. Nd6 Kc7
{ I like this active pawn sacrifice, which maintains the bishop pair. Instead  12...Bxd6  13.Rxd6  Rb8  is the main line. White can secure the b-pawn with  14.b3  or  14.Rd2  and aspire for a tiny advantage. }
13. Nxf7 Rg8
{ Now White can either extract his knight or get going with his kingside development. }
14. Ne5 { This is the main line. The knight heads home. } 14... Rb8
{ Black has to play for activity! } 15. Nxd7
{ This eliminates Black's bishop pair and avoids losing more time with the e5-knight. }
15... Nxd7 16. g3
{ White looks to catch up in development rather than worrying about the b2-pawn. }
16... Rxb2 17. Bh3
{ The best try. White gains time by attacking the d7-knight. } 17... Nf6
{ Black has also tried  17...Nc5  18.O-O  Bd6  which is fine, but I prefer to keep the  a3-f8 diagonal open for our bishop. }
18. O-O { There is still no time for  18.gxf4  Bb4  -+ } 18... Bb4 19. Rc1 Rd8
{ Planning to come into d2. } 20. Bg2
{ White looks for counterplay against the c6-pawn. } 20... Rdd2
{ Still delaying the exchange on g3!   If  20...fxg3  21.hxg3  Rdd2  White has  22.Nd1!?  Rbc2  23.Ne3  with the better pawn structure. }
21. gxf4 Rbc2
{ Black has some initiative. White should bail out while he can. } 22. Ne4 Rxe2
23. Nxf6 gxf6 24. Rxc2 Rxc2 25. Be4
{ An important point. White gets a passed pawn of his own. Without this move Black would be much better. }
25... Rxa2 26. Rc1 c5 27. Bxh7 Rd2 28. h4 a5
{ This still look like anything could happen but the game headed towards a draw in Nakamura - Kramnik, Tal Memorial, Moscow 2012. }
*

