{ We will often play this active 'Nimzo-like' move when we can. Other moves like  6...d5  and  6...Be7  are also fine. }
7. Nb5
{ This is a typical idea. White guards against doubled c-pawns and eyes the d6-square. }
7... a6 { Calling White's bluff.  7...O-O  and  7...d5  are fine too. } 8. Nd6+
Ke7 9. Nxc8+ Rxc8
{ Black had to move his king, but it's perfectly safe. White is way behind in development and must play carefully. }
10. Bd2 Bxc3 { This is more interesting than  10...d5  11.cxd5  Nxd5= } 11.
Bxc3 Ne4 12. Bxg7 { This runs into all kinds of trouble. } 12... Qa5+ 13. Ke2
Rhg8 { The bishop is short of squares. } 14. Bd4
{ If  14.Bh6  Black strikes from the other side -  14...Qh5  nabs the bishop. }
14... Nxd4+ 15. Qxd4
{ Or  15.exd4  Rxc4  -+ with a strong attack. White is not even up a pawn anymore. }
15... Rxc4 { Anyway! } 16. Qxc4 Qd2+ 17. Kf3 Qxf2+ 18. Kxe4 d5+ { and wins. } *

