[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 20: White avoids the Four Knights - 5.g3"]
[Black "8.a3 Bxc3+ 9.Nxc3 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arise after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2.e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ This will be our move order. Instead  2...Nf6  really would reduce our options.  I think 2... Nf6 is a good move if Black is aiming for a quick ...d5, which is a favorite method of Grunfeld players, or a Hedgehog setup with ...b6, a favorite of Nimzo/Queen's Indian players, in which case the c6-knight would not be well placed.   Another option is  2...g6  , but that allows White to set up a Maroczy Bind with  3.e4  Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Bg7  6.Be3  Having played both sides here, I consider this to be favorable for White. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. g3
{ This is a tricky move order if Black is not prepared. The main lines of the Four Knights have held up very well for Black for a long time, so White tries to avoid them with this typical English move. }
5... e5
{ A very direct attempt to challenge White's move order. Instead  5...e6  6.Bg2  Qb6  is still possible, but it's not quite the same thing.  (There is no ...Bb4 threatening to White's double pawns - White could answer the check with Bd2 for example, and after ... Ne5, there is certainly no ...Qc6 possibility!) }
6. Nb5
{ Other moves offer no challenge whatsoever.  6.Nc2  d5!  7.cxd5  Qxd5  8.Qxd5  Nxd5=  is certainly no problem. Black has more space in a symmetrical structure.   6.Nxc6?!  dxc6!  7.Qxd8+  Kxd8  is even better for Black. This is a good structure. Black will follow with moves like  ...Kc7, ...Be6, ...a5, ...Nd7. }
6... Bb4+ { This is surprisingly disruptive. } 7. N1c3 { A natural move. } 7...
d6
{ Black is prepared to give up his b4-bishop, as he develops quickly in this line. }
8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. Nxc3 Be6
{ Black's 'Sveshnikov' structure may not appeal to some, but Black has such smooth development he is doing well. Even though White has the bishop pair Black should not refrain from opening the position because White is not really ready for it. If White tends to his c4-pawn he can quickly come under pressure. }
10. Bg2 { White does best to get caught up in development. } 10... Bxc4 11. Bg5
O-O 12. Rc1 Rc8
{ Another way to play is  12...h6  13.Bxf6  Qxf6  14.Ne4  Qe6  when White can win back the pawn, but there is no advantage.  15.Qxd6  Nd4!  16.Qxe6  Bxe6  17.Nc5  Rac8!  18.Bxb7  Rb8=  19.e3   or  19.f3  Bc8!?  20.Bxc8  Rfxc8  21.b4  a5=  and if  22.bxa5 ?!  Rb2  -/+  19...Nb3  when Black is fine. White is behind in development and can hardly consolidate the extra pawn.  20.Nxb3  Rxb7  21.Nc5  Rxb2  22.Nxe6  fxe6  23.O-O  Rb3=  The doubled e-pawns are of little consequence, as Black is 'ahead' in activating his rooks. }
13. O-O
{ Rather than trading pieces to regain the pawn, White hopes to get some pressure with his active pieces. }
13... Nd4 { Black also plays for activity. } 14. Bxb7 Rb8 15. Bd5 Nxd5
{ A cool sacrifice.  15...Bxd5  is also possible, but White has some initiative after  16.Nxd5  . }
16. Bxd8 Nxc3 17. bxc3 Nxe2+ 18. Kg2 Nxc1 19. Bg5
{ This is necessary. If  19.Re1  Nd3  -/+ or  19.Qxc1  Bxf1+  20.Qxf1  Rfxd8  -/+ }
19... Nd3
{ This keeps the game complex and it is probably objectively the strongest. After  19...Bxf1+  20.Kxf1  Nb3  21.Qxd6  White had some initiative in Vitiugov - Leko, Linares 2018, although Black held rather easily. }
20. Qg4 Be6 21. Qf3 { 21.Qd1  Bc4  repeats. } 21... Nb2
{ Or  21...Bc4  22.Qc6  d5= } 22. Be7 Rfe8 23. Bxd6
{ This bishop gets a bit stuck. } 23... Rbd8
{ Black has very good counterchances. } 24. Qc6 { Forced. } 24... h6
{ Not the only move, but we'll follow a correspondence game for a bit. 'A queen is a queen' but there are no real targets and Black has safer king. }
25. h3 Rc8 26. Qb7 Nc4 { White has to play with great care. } 27. Qa6
{ 27.Bb4?  a5∓  traps the bishop. } 27... Red8 28. Rd1
{ White self-pins. Instead  28.Bb4  e4!  sees Black developing a strong attack with ...Rd2 and ...e3. }
28... Ra8
{ A sneaky move. Instead  28...Nb6  was fine for Black in Koestner - Loeffler, email 2016. }
29. Qb7 { Practically forced. } 29... a5
{ 29...Rac8  would allow White to wisely repeat moves. } 30. Bc7
{ A tactical way out of the pin. } 30... Rxd1 31. Qxa8+ Kh7
{ That ...h6 came in handy! } 32. f3 Bd5 { Black has great play. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 20: White avoids the Four Knights - 5.g3"]
[Black "7.Bd2 a6 8.N5c3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English can be rather annoying to meet if the black player does not like the reversed Sicilians that arise after 1....e5. English players can be a tricky bunch - I know as I am one of them! - because White can often choose between transposing back into 1. d4 main lines, or go for an independent course. As a King's Indian player, I have generally been happy to play 1... g6, which keeps a lot of flexibility if White stays with a pure 'English' course. My solid Black opening was always the Slav, and I never really liked 1... c6 here because I am not a big fan of the English/Reti Slavs for Black that arise after 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 or 3. e3.In this course I will recommend the principled 1... c5, when we no longer have to worry about White sneaking back into some 1. d4 main lines. We will look at strong theoretical lines rather than trying to do something tricky. This course could also be useful against 1. Nf3 because Black can play 1... c5. Then 2. c4 will bring us right back into our repertoire. White can also play 2.e4 however, and I thought covering the Najdorf Sicilian in this course may be a bit too much! }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ This will be our move order. Instead  2...Nf6  really would reduce our options.  I think 2... Nf6 is a good move if Black is aiming for a quick ...d5, which is a favorite method of Grunfeld players, or a Hedgehog setup with ...b6, a favorite of Nimzo/Queen's Indian players, in which case the c6-knight would not be well placed.   Another option is  2...g6  , but that allows White to set up a Maroczy Bind with  3.e4  Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Bg7  6.Be3  Having played both sides here, I consider this to be favorable for White. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. g3
{ This is a tricky move order if Black is not prepared. The main lines of the Four Knights have held up very well for Black for a long time, so White tries to avoid them with this typical English move. }
5... e5
{ A very direct attempt to challenge White's move order. Instead  5...e6  6.Bg2  Qb6  is still possible, but it's not quite the same thing.  (There is no ...Bb4 threatening to White's double pawns - White could answer the check with Bd2 for example, and after ... Ne5, there is certainly no ...Qc6 possibility!) }
6. Nb5
{ Other moves offer no challenge whatsoever.  6.Nc2  d5!  7.cxd5  Qxd5  8.Qxd5  Nxd5=  is certainly no problem. Black has more space in a symmetrical structure.   6.Nxc6?!  dxc6!  7.Qxd8+  Kxd8  is even better for Black. This is a good structure. Black will follow with moves like  ...Kc7, ...Be6, ...a5, ...Nd7. }
6... Bb4+ { This is surprisingly disruptive. } 7. Bd2
{ White wants to exchange the bishops to exploit the weakened d6-square. Black does not have to cooperate. }
7... a6 { The key move. } 8. N5c3
{ This is the safe choice, but White's king knight is now on c3. Black can already strike back in the center. }
8... d5 { This is the most direct.  8...d6  9.Bg2  Be6  is also possible. } 9.
cxd5 Nxd5 10. Bg2 Be6 11. O-O Nb6
{ Black has also tried  11...O-O  . The simplifications that occur after  12.Nxd5  Bxd5  13.Bxb4  Bxg2  14.Kxg2  Nxb4  15.Qb3  Qd5  16.Qxd5  Nxd5  17.Nd2  Rac8  18.Rac1  f6  should allow Black to equalize, but it's not very interesting. }
12. Na4
{ This is the only move that is at all testing. Black does not face problems after  12.Be3  Nc4  , as in Aronian - Nakamura, London 2012 or  12.Ne4  Be7!  , as played in Shchekachev -Edouard, Caen 2011.  In both cases ...Nc4 is coming. Black won both games.   Instead  12.Na3  looks strange.  12...O-O  13.Nc2  Be7  14.Be3  Nc4  was fine for Black in Feller - Vocaturo, Germany 2017. }
12... Bxd2
{ I prefer this to the more common  12...Be7  . After  13.Nbc3  Nxa4   White had the initiative after  13...O-O  14.Nxb6  Qxb6  15.Nd5  in Iturrizaga Bonelli - Rodshtein, Baku 2015  14.Nxa4  O-O  15.Be3  Rc8  16.Bb6  Qxd1  17.Rfxd1  f5  This may be ok, but the text move is simpler. }
13. Nxb6 Qxb6 14. Qxd2 Rd8 15. Qc1 O-O
{ This is just nice for Black - space and some initiative. } *

