1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nc6 3. Nc3 e5 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. d3 d6 7. Bd2 Nge7 8. a3
O-O 9. Rb1 a5 10. O-O Rb8 11. Ne1 Be6 12. Nc2 d5
{ Of course. We will play this pretty much any time we're given the chance to do so. }
13. cxd5 Nxd5
{ We have the desired structure. Black scores well over 50% here. } 14. Nxd5
Bxd5 15. Bxd5 Qxd5 16. b4 cxb4 { Another idea is   16...b5!? } 17. axb4 b6 18.
Ne3
{ in the theory section we also cover   18.Bc3  Rfd8  Altounian-Yermolinsky, San Diego 2004 }
18... Qe6 19. Nc4 axb4 20. Bxb4 Rfd8
{ Black has more space and is well placed. The b-pawn is an asset. } 21. Nd2 b5
22. Bc3 { If   22.Ne4  f5  23.Nc5  Qd5 } 22... b4 23. Ba1 Bh6
{ Another possibility is   23...e4!?  24.Nxe4  Bxa1  25.Rxa1  b3 } 24. Nb3 Rbc8
25. e3
{ The computer tries to hold with   25.Nc5  Qe7  26.Ne4  f5  27.Nd2  but who would play like that? }
25... Qd5 26. d4 exd4 27. Nxd4 Qe4 { 27...Bg7∓  is simple and good. } 28. Rb3
Ne5 29. f4
{ White can hold with   29.Qb1!  Rxd4  30.exd4  30...Nf3+  as now White has  31.Rxf3  Qxf3  32.Qxb4 }
29... Nc4 { The e3-pawn is too weak, as is White's king. } 30. Qe2 Bf8 31. Rd1
Re8 32. Kf2 Bc5 33. Qd3 Qd5 34. Re1 Ra8
{ There was a nice combination with   34...Nxe3  35.Rxe3  Rxe3  and Black's queen comes in.  36.Qxe3   36.Kxe3  Qg2  Qh1 }
35. Nc2 Qxd3 36. Rxd3 Ra2 37. Re2 Nxe3 38. Nxe3 Rxa1 39. Rc2 Ba7 40. Kf3 Bxe3
41. Rxe3 Ra3 { 41...Ra3  42.Rxa3  bxa3  43.Ra2  Ra8 } *

