1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 e5 6. O-O d6 7. a3 a5 8. d3 Nge7
9. Ne1 Be6 10. Nc2 d5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Ne3 Nb6
{ In this exact position this is the correct retreat.   12...Nde7  is the normal move, and it is playable as well. }
13. Bd2
{ 13.Bxc6+!?  This is White's main try, and probably the most challenging move. }
13... Nd4 { with counterplay based on the b3-square. } 14. Bxb7 Rb8 15. Bg2 Bb3
{ 15...f5!?  16.Rc1?  O-O  17.f4  exf4  18.gxf4  Re8∓  Spoelman-Bok, Amsterdam 2015 }
16. Qe1 f5 17. Rc1 O-O 18. Nc4
{ White gives up some material to get some breathing room. } 18... Nxc4 19.
Bd5+ Kh8 20. dxc4 Nc2 21. Rxc2 Bxc2 22. Qc1 Bb3
{ White does not have quite enough compensation, but the position is still complex. }
23. e4
{ This cements the position of White's bishop - away from his king's defense. }
23... f4 24. Kg2 g5 25. g4 h5 26. h3 Rf6 27. f3 Rh6 28. Ne2 Ba4
{ 28...a4  was possible too. Probably Black thought his bishop would be out of play. }
29. Bc3 Be8 { Black is just much better after   29...Bf6 } 30. Qd2 a4 31. Nc1
Qe7 32. Nd3 { Matters are not so simple now. } 32... Bc6 33. Re1
{ This dissuades Black from taking on d5, but   33.Qf2  Rc8  34.Rd1  was stronger. }
33... Rc8 34. Qf2 Bf6 35. Qd2 { White does not sense the danger.   35.Rh1 }
35... hxg4 36. hxg4 { A strange blunder.   36.fxg4 } 36... Qh7 37. Nf2 Rh2+ 38.
Kf1 Qh4 39. Bxc6 Qg3 *

