1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nf3 e5 6. O-O d6 7. a3 a5 8. d3 Nge7
9. Ne1 Be6 10. Nc2 d5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Ne3 Nb6 13. Bxc6+
{ This is the most testing idea, but giving up the bishop carries certain risks of course. }
13... bxc6 14. Ne4 c4
{ Black is losing the pawn anyway, but he will be able to attack in on c4. }
15. Nxc4 Nxc4 16. dxc4 O-O
{ Not   16...Bxc4??  17.Nd6+  Black could also play   16...Qd4  17.Qxd4  exd4  18.Bd2  O-O  =∞ }
17. Nc5 Qxd1
{ I think Black has sufficient play after   17...Bh3!?  18.Re1  Qe7  19.Ne4  19...f5  20.Qd6  Qxd6  21.Nxd6  Rfb8=∞ }
18. Rxd1 Bxc4 19. Rd2 Rfd8 20. Rc2 Rd1+ 21. Kg2 Rd4
{ 21...Ba6  hopes to keep the bishop, and  22.Nxa6  Rxa6  is ok for Black. }
22. e4 { White will catch an exchange. } 22... a4 { 22...f5!? } 23. Be3 Rxe4
24. Nxe4 { A better way was   24.Kg1!?  Bd5  25.Nxe4  Bxe4  26.Rc4 } 24... Bd3
25. Rd2 Bxe4+ 26. f3 Bd5
{ Now Black's compensation is sufficient, and his play seem easier. } 27. Rc1
f5 28. Kf2 Kf7 29. Re2 Rb8 30. Bc5 Rb3 31. Rc3 Rb5 32. Bb4 e4 33. fxe4 Bd4+ 34.
Ke1 fxe4 { More ambitious than   34...Bxc3+  35.Bxc3  Bxe4=+ } 35. Rc1 c5 36.
Bc3 { 36.Rd1!  was the best try. } 36... Ke6 37. Rd2 Ke5
{ There was nothing wrong with   37...Be3 } 38. Re2
{ 38.Rcd1!  keeps the fight going. } 38... Rb8 39. Rf2 e3 40. Rf4 g5 41. Rg4 h6
42. Rd1 Bxc3+ 43. bxc3 Bf3 44. Rc4 Rb2 45. Rxc5+ Ke6
{ Black wins after   45...Ke6  46.Rc8  Re2+  47.Kf1  Rf2+  48.Ke1  Rf1+!  49.Kxf1  e2+ }
*

