1. c4 c5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. a3 d6 6. Rb1 a5 7. e3 e5 8. d3 Nge7
9. Nge2 O-O 10. O-O Rb8
{ A very important idea to understand.   10...Be6?!  is a tempo short.  11.Nd5  Rb8  12.Nec3+=  with a lasting grip. }
11. Bd2 Be6 12. Qb3
{ This brings coverage to the d5- and b5-squares, but blocks the b-pawn.   12.Nd5  12...Bf5!?  is an interesting idea. }
12... f5 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. cxd5 Bf7 15. Qc2
{ 15.f4!?  was played in M.Gurevich - Gelashvili, Kocaeli 2002  15...exf4  16.Nxf4  b5∞ }
15... Ne7 16. e4 b5 { Black should be fine here. } 17. Be3 Kh8 18. b4
{ 18.f4  looks better. } 18... cxb4 19. axb4 a4 20. Qd2 fxe4
{ Black could also keep the tension with   20...Nc8  first. } 21. dxe4 Nc8 22.
Bg5
{ Here White has an interesting try with   22.Rfc1  Nb6  23.Bf1  23...Nc4  24.Rxc4!  bxc4  25.b5=∞ }
22... Qd7 23. f4 { This leaves the bishop sidelined.   23.Rfc1 } 23... h6 24.
Bh4 Nb6 25. Kh1 Nc4 26. Qc1 exf4 27. gxf4 Qg4 { White loses material. } 28. Qe1
{ The only way to cover both pieces. } 28... Ne3 29. Bf3 Qh3
{ A funny position! Whtie cannot protect everything. } 30. Qf2 Nxf1 31. Rxf1
Qd7 32. Qg2 Rbe8 33. Bg4 Qa7 34. f5 gxf5 35. exf5 Rg8 36. Bf3 a3 37. Bf2 Qe7
