1. c4 g6 2. g3 Bg7 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nc3 O-O 5. e4 c5 6. Nge2 Nc6 7. d3 a6 8. O-O
Rb8 9. a4 d6 10. h3 Bd7 11. Be3 e5
{ I made this up at the board, and it's pretty good. This move is also not considered in Marin's series on the English Opening for White. We now have a 'double Botvinnnik' of sorts, but Black's knight is on the f6-square. This could be conisdered to be misplaced, but I do not think matters are so simple. In this structure, pushing the f-pawn is not always so great, as a subsequent exf5/...exf4 opens the diagonal for a blocked bishop. Decades of playing the Botvinnik setup has also taught me to be careful with the e7-knight, as it is not always so manoueverable. The f6-knight has potential pathways to improvement, most notably with ...Ne8-c7. Lastly, in this pawn structure, the move Be3/Be6 can be premature, as Nd5/...Nd4 can be annoying because capturing with a knight would lose a piece. Here White's bishop is already on e3, while our bishop is on the d7-square. I know sometimes this means it's more passive, but here I'll say it's more flexible! }
12. f4 exf4 13. Nxf4
{ 13.gxf4  Nh5=+  is nice for Black. This idea is well known from the Closed Sicilian.   13.Bxf4  Be6  14.Qd2  14...Qc7  N  15.Nd5  Bxd5  16.exd5  Na5!  is very nice for Black. }
13... Ne8 14. Nfd5 Nc7 15. Rb1
{ 15.Nxc7  Qxc7  16.Nd5  Qd8=+  when the only bad minor piece is the g2-bishop. This is basically the theme of the game. }
15... Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Be6 { 16...b5=+ } 17. Qd2 Bxd5 18. exd5 Nd4 19. Bg5 Qd7 20.
Rbe1 Rfe8 21. a5 Qc7 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. Re1 Rxe1+ 24. Qxe1 Be5 25. h4 h5 26.
Kh2 b6 { Opening a second front. } 27. axb6 Qxb6 28. Qd2 Nf5 29. Bf4 Bxf4 30.
gxf4 Qd8 31. Qf2 Nxh4
{ White has set a little trap.   31...Qxh4+?!  32.Qxh4  Nxh4  33.Be4  33...Nf5?  34.Bxf5  gxf5  with an extra pawn, but Black cannot win.   31...Qf6!?  is good. }
32. d4 cxd4 33. Qxd4 Nf5 34. Qf2 a5 { 34...Qe7!  was stronger. } 35. Bh3 Qf6
36. Bxf5 Qxf5 37. Qd2 Kf8 38. Qd4 { 38.c5!  dxc5  39.d6  with counterplay. }
38... a4 39. c5 Qc2+ 40. Kg3 Qxc5 { Now it's over. } 41. Qxa4 Qe3+ 42. Kg2 Qe2+
43. Kg3 Qxb2 44. Qc6 Qf6 45. Qc4 Kg7 46. Kh3 Kh6 47. Qe4 Qc3+ 48. Kg2 h4 49. f5
Qg3+ 50. Kf1 Qh3+ 51. Ke2 Qxf5 52. Qe7 Qxd5 53. Qf8+ Kg5 54. Qe7+ Kg4 55. Kf2
h3 56. Qe2+ Kh4 57. Qe3 *

