{ Somehow I had just beat three GM's in a row, and I now had Black vs. the #19 player in the world. Smirin usually plays 1.e4. }
1. c4 g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 3. Nc3 c5 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 6. Nc2 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Qa5
8. Bd2 Nf6 9. f3 d6 10. e4 Be6
{ This was a novelty at the time, but a very obvious move of course. } 11. Ne3
{ The direct   11.Nd4  Rc8  12.Nxe6  fxe6  13.Qb3  is well met with  13...Qc5  N }
11... Rc8 12. Rb1
{ After   12.Nd5  it turns out that Black can play  12...Ne5!?  without fearing  13.Nxf6+  exf6 }
12... b6 13. Nd5 Nd7 14. h4 { Creative perhaps, but not really dangerous. }
14... Nc5 15. Qc2 Qa4 { There is also an active possibility with   15...f5!? }
16. Qxa4 Nxa4 17. h5 Rg8 18. hxg6 hxg6 19. Bg5 Nc5
{ 19...Kd7?  20.c5!  Nxc5  21.Bb5±  ties Black up.   19...f6!?  was possible, but I was scared of the tactics.  20.Bxf6  exf6  21.Nxf6+  Kf7  22.Nxg8  Kxg8=+ }
20. Kd2 Kd7
{ I like this idea. Black can fight for the file that White openened. } 21. Be2
Rh8 22. Rhd1 f6 23. Be3 Ke8 24. Rh1 { 24.Bxc5  dxc5∓ } 24... Kf7 25. Bd4 Bd7
26. Bf2 Na5 27. Ke3 Na4 28. Kd2 Nc5
{ Sensing the dangers, Smirin acqueisces to a draw against his lowly opponent.  After the game I found the shot   28...Nb2-+  29.Rxh8  Nbxc4+  30.Bxc4  Nxc4+  31.Kd3  Ne5+ }
29. Ke3 Na4 30. Kd2 *

