[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 4. e3 Nf6 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8.
Qb3 Nxc3 9. Bc4 Nd5 10. Bxd5 e6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. O-O Qd5 13. Qc3 f6
{ This move looks very surprising at first. Black makes another pawn move while he only has his queen out and White has already castled. The little pawn move covers the e4- and g5-squares so White’s f3-knight if rather ineffective. Often Black will just put his king on f7 where it is actually quite safe while also covering the pawns on the third rank. }
14. Be3 a5
{ This is not so terrible, but it can certainly wait. Black could play the flexible   14...Be7! }
15. Nd2 Bb4
{ This was Black’s idea. However, white queen turns out to be more useful on the c2-square as it supports the coming knight manouver. }
16. Qc2 Kf7 17. Ne4 Ba6 18. Rfc1 Rhc8 19. f3
{ This not only stabilizes the knight, but is prepares to swing the queen to the kingside. }
19... Rab8 { 19...Be7 } 20. Qf2 Be7 21. b3
{ A simple waiting move that just slightly improves White’s position. Lenderman heaped praise upon this little move after the game.  Already White could force a draw with   21.Qh4  h5  22.Rc5  Qd8  23.Rxh5  gxh5  24.Qxh5+  but there is no reason to do so. }
21... Rd8
{ Black does not sense the danger and he moves the rook to an unfortunate square, as the c6-pawn will lack protection.  Better was   21...Kg7  22.Nc5  Ra8 }
22. Qh4 Rh8
{ Now Lenderman realized what was happening, but it is too late.   22...h5  23.Rc5!   22...Kg7  23.Bh6+  Kf7  24.Bf4! }
23. Rc5 Qd8
{ The rook is untouchable:   23...Bxc5  24.Qxf6+  Kg8  25.dxc5+-  gives White an overwhelming position. So Black’s queen has so lose touch with either the a5- or c6-pawns. }
24. Rxc6 Bb7 { 24...f5?  25.Ng5+ } 25. Rc2 Rc8 26. Rxc8 Qxc8 27. Rc1 Qb8 28. h3
{ 28.Bf4  Qa7?   28...Qd8  29.Nd6+!  Bxd6   29...Kg8  30.Nxb7  Qxb7  31.Rc7  30.Bxd6  and the d4-pawn is covered }
28... h5 29. Bf4 Qd8 30. Qf2 g5 31. Bg3 g4 32. hxg4 hxg4 33. Rc7 Bxe4 34. fxe4
Rh5
{ Black hopes to get in …Qh8 with some counterplay, but White has an immediate breakthrough. }
35. d5 exd5 36. Qc5 *

