1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. g3 Qb6 7. Nb3 Ne5 8. e4
Bb4 9. Qe2 d6 10. f4 Nc6 11. Be3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qc7 13. Bg2 e5
{ Blocking e4-e5 and taking a stand on the dark-squares. If allowed, Black will follow up with ...b6 to prevent c4-c5. Then ...Be6 or ...Ba6 will lay siege to the c4-pawn.   13...b6?!  14.e5!  causes problems.   13...O-O  is the older move, and this remains quite playable. }
14. c5
{ White plays this while he can. The alternatives are covered in the course.   14.O-O  b6!   14.f5  b6! }
14... b6
{ This is still a good move. Black eliminates the cramping effect of the c5-pawn to gain some space for his pieces. }
15. cxd6 Qxd6 16. O-O O-O 17. f5 { Too straightforward. } 17... Rd8
{ 17...Qa3!  is good here too.  18.Qb5  Ba6!  19.Qxc6  Rac8∓  but the endgame is worse for White. }
18. Rfd1 { If   18.g4  Qd3∓  and White's position is creaking at the seams. }
18... Qa3 19. Rxd8+ Nxd8 20. Bg5
{ 20.Qb5  Qd6  controlling the d-file and planning ...Bb7 is also nice for Black. }
20... Ba6 { with a great position for Black. } 21. Qd2 Qe7 22. Rd1
{ I believe   22.Bf1  has been suggested as a grovelling attempt, but  22...Bxf1  23.Rxf1  Nb7  intending ...Rc8 or ...Rc8 still leaves Black clearly in the driver's seat.  Black is also doing well after   22.Bxf6  Qxf6  23.Bf1  Bb7∓ }
22... Nb7 23. Bf3 Rd8 24. Qc1 Rxd1+ 25. Bxd1 Nd6 26. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Not allowing any counterplay. If   26...Qxf6  27.Qa3 } 27. Qe3 Qc7 28. a4 Qd7
{ 28...Qc4  29.Nd2  Qd3-+  is winning too. } 29. a5 Nxe4 30. Bc2 Qb5 31. Qf3
Ng5 32. Qg2 bxa5 *

