1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 6. g3 Qb6 7. Ndb5 Ne5 8.
Bg2 a6 9. Na4 Qd8 10. Nd6+ Bxd6 11. Qxd6 Nxc4 12. Qc5 d5 13. b3 Bd7
{ A useful counterattack which also prepares ...Rc8. } 14. bxc4 Bxa4 15. cxd5
Nxd5 16. O-O
{ White has some compensation with his bishop pair and development lead, but with a few careful moves Black can neutralize the pressure. }
16... Qd7
{ Note that   16...Rc8?  17.Qd4  with a double attack on a4 and g7.  The immediate   16...f6!?  is possible though. }
17. Ba3
{ 17.Qd4  O-O  18.Bb2  f6  and everything is in order.   17.Bd2  Rc8  18.Qa3  f6  and again everything is fine. }
17... Rc8
{ This is not only an obvious move, but it's an essential one because Black with often need to meet e4 with ...Nc3. }
18. Qd4 f6
{ This position has been seen a few times in practice. Ori Kobo played it twice with White. }
19. Bh3
{ tries to pressure the e6-pawn, but   19.Rac1  Kf7  20.e4?!  Nc3  works out well for Black.   19.Qg4  was tried in a correspondence game.  19...Kf7  looks right here too.   19.Bf3!?  Introducing the possibility of Bh5+. The e2-pawn also gets some protection, and White has some luft for his king.  19...Kf7! }
19... Kf7 { was part of Black's plan anyway. } 20. Bb2 Rhd8 21. Rac1 Ne7 22.
Qg4 Ng6 23. f3 { 23.Bg2   23.Bc3 } 23... h5 { 23...Bb5 } 24. Qb4
