1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 6. g3 Qb6 7. Ndb5 Ne5 8.
Bg2 a6 9. Qa4 Rb8 10. Be3 Bc5
{ Do not fall for this little trick: 10...axb5? 11.Bxb6 bxa4 12.Bc7!+/ - } 11.
Bxc5 Qxc5 12. Qa3
{ 12.Na3  O-O  Black has a great position with ...d6, ...Bd7, and ...b5 in mind. }
12... b6 { Black is a bit worse after   12...Qxa3  13.Nxa3+= } 13. Nd6+ Ke7 14.
Qxc5 bxc5 15. Nxc8+
{ 15.O-O-O  Neg4!  the attack on the f2-pawn is not easy to deal with. } 15...
Rhxc8
{ Black has mobilized with great speed and has nice play in the endgame. I would not expect many White players to go for this. It's not the kind of position one would stumble into, and White has more enterprising ways to play. }
16. b3 d5 { This is not the only possibility, but it's the most aggressive. }
17. cxd5 c4
{ White has to be quite careful here or his queenside will fall apart. Black's knights are very active, while the g2-bishop can't help defend White's queenside. }
18. b4
{ White is trying to reduce Black's initiative by keeping the c-file closed.   18.bxc4?!  is asking too much of the position. Even though the queens are gone, we rarely see White so far behind in development @@StartBracket@@compare the rooks!@@EndBracket@@ at this stage of the game.  18...Rxc4  19.Rc1  Rbc8  20.Kd2  Neg4→  is really disruptive. If  21.f3?!  Rd4+  22.Ke1  Ne3∓   18.Kd2  is another way to return the pawn.  18...cxb3  19.axb3  Rxb3  20.Rhc1  Nc4+  21.Kc2  Rb2+   21...Rb6  22.dxe6  fxe6=  22.Kd1  a5⇆ }
18... Rxb4 { This is the most natural. } 19. h3
{ To cover the g4-square.   19.O-O-O  looks crazy but it's not so bad.  19...Neg4⇆  still gives Black good play and I don't think we'll find any takers for White's position.   19.dxe6  fxe6  20.h3  Nf7!?  also gives Black an active position. }
19... Ne8 { 19...Ned7!  20.dxe6  fxe6⇆ } 20. f4 Nd7 21. dxe6 fxe6 22. Be4
