1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 6. Ndb5 d5 7. Bf4 e5 8.
cxd5 exf4 9. dxc6 bxc6 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Nd4 Bd7
{ I like this move the best. MVL has played 11...Bb7, but this blocks the b-file and I don't think it's so easy for Black. 11...Kc7 is flexible though, and not a bad alternative. }
12. g3
{ This is typically how White week seek to develop his kingside. 12.e3 fxe3 will leave White with a vulnerable e-pawn. By playing g3, White hopes to encourage Black to take on g3 and open the h-file for White's rook. Black can indeed take, but often there is no rush to do so as the f4-pawn controls e3 which can be a nuisance for White. }
12... Rb8
{ Activating the rook.  Instead   12...fxg3  13.hxg3  Rb8  14.O-O-O  Kc7  gives White some extra options, such as  15.Bh3!?  or even   15.Rd2!?  covering the b2-pawn and allowing for e2-e3 to protect the f2-pawn, which we will see is often vulnerable when White castles queenside. }
13. O-O-O
{ Protecting the b2-pawn and activating the rook. Now the f2-pawn will be a target however. }
13... Kc7
{ Leaving the f4-pawn to its fate. White can indeed take it, but it costs a tempo. }
14. gxf4 Ng4
{ Play will be rather complicated now, but there are some recurring ideas. }
15. Ne4 { 15.Rd2  avoids a fork.  15...Nxf2  16.Rg1  g6  17.Bg2  Bc5= } 15...
Re8
{ Not   15...f5?  16.h3!  fxe4  17.hxg4  Bxg4  18.Bh3  and White has a strong initiative. }
16. f3 Ne3
{ The knight is a nuisance here. Do not be tempted by 16...Rxe4? 17.fxe4 Nf2 when 18.Bg2! is nice for White. }
17. Rd3 Nd5 { now hitting the f4-pawn. } 18. Nb5+
{ It's interesting how both sides are compelled to force the pace even though no one has completed development.   18.e3?  f5!  now works.   18.f5  g6!  This is often a good move, as ...Bh6 can cause problems.  19.f6  c5  20.Nc2  Bc6  21.e3  can be bet with  21...Nb6  22.Bg2  Re6=  when ...Bxe4 and ... Rxf6 will regain the pawn with a good position. }
18... cxb5 19. Rxd5 Bc6 { 19...a6!?  is also possible. } 20. Rd2
{ 20.Rf5  is a better try, but Black is fine after  20...Re7!  Intending ...g6 and ...Bh6. The White rook is awkwardly placed. For example  21.Nc3  g6  22.Nd5+  Bxd5  23.Rxd5  Bh6  24.Rxb5?!  better was   24.e4  Bxf4+  25.Kc2  a6  =/=/+  Bxf4+  25.Kc2  Rd8→  with the initiative. }
20... f5 21. Ng3 { 21.Nc3  a6 } 21... g6
{ Now ...Bh6 is coming and Black is much better with the bishop pair and superior pawn structure. }
22. e4 Bh6 23. Rc2 { 23.Ne2  fxe4-+ } 23... Kb6 24. Bg2 Bxf4+ 25. Kb1 fxe4 26.
Nxe4 Re5 { 26...Rd8 } 27. Rd1 Rd5 28. Rxd5 Bxd5 29. Bf1 Rd8 30. Re2 Bf7
{ 30...Be6 } 31. Nc3 b4 32. Re4 Bd6 33. Na4+ Kc7 34. Bc4 Be8 35. Bb3 Bb5 36.
Re1 Rf8 { 36...Bxh2  37.Re7+   37.Rh1  Rd2  Rd7 } 37. Rc1+ Kb8 38. Rd1 Rf6 39.
a3 Be2 40. Re1 Bxf3 41. axb4 Bxb4 42. Re8+ Kb7 43. Rh8 Be4+ 44. Ka2 g5 45. Rg8
Rg6 46. Rd8 Bc6 47. Rh8 Rg7 48. Nc3 Rd7 { 48...Bd6 } 49. Be6 { 49.h3 } 49...
Bxc3 50. bxc3 Rd2+ 51. Ka3 Rxh2 52. Rg8 h6 53. Kb4 Kb6 54. c4 a5+ 55. Kc3 Kc5
