[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. Ndb5
{ This is an important move. White takes aim at the d6- and c7-squares. } 6...
d5
{ After 6...d6 7. Bf4 forces 7...e5, and then 8.Bg5 gives secures control of the d5-square and gives White a pleasant advantage. }
7. Bf4
{ This is more critical than greedy pawn grabbing with 7.cxd5. There's a little threat with Nc7+, so Black's reply is forced. }
7... e5 8. cxd5 exf4 9. dxc6 bxc6
{ We cannot trade queens ourselves because Nc7+ would still hang over our head. So we have to allow our king to be displaced. }
10. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is an important position. Black's king is a little bit exposed and his pawn structure is broken. However, he has the bishop pair and open lines for his rooks. It's dynamically equal, and Black has decent chances of taking the initiative. }
11. Rd1+
{ This is the most common choice. White activates the rook, but keeps the f2-pawn guarded. Black has more than one way to equalize. }
11... Bd7
{ Here 11...Ke7 is not as good. After 12.Nd4 Bd7 13.g3 we do not have ...Ng4 with such effect because the f2-pawn is covered, so Black lacks counterplay. }
12. Nd6
{ Black quickly obtains the initiative after   12.Nd4?!  Kc7  13.g3  Rb8  with ...Bb4 coming. }
12... Kc7
{ I like this active pawn sacrifice, which maintains the bishop pair. Instead 12...Bxd6 13.Rxd6 Rb8 is the main line. White can secure the b-pawn with 14.b3 or 14.Rd2 and aspire for a tiny advantage. }
13. Nxf7 Rg8
{ Now White can extract his knight, or get going with his kingside development. }
14. Ne5 { 14.g3  Rb8! } 14... Rb8 { Black has to play for activity! } 15. Nxd7
{ This eliminates Black's bishop pair and avoids losing more time with the e5-knight.   15.Nd3?!   15.Rd2 }
15... Nxd7 16. g3
{ White looks to catch up in development rather than worrying about the b2-pawn.   16.Rd2  protects the b2-pawn.  16...Ne5  With the idea ...Nc4.  17.Rc2   17.e3  fxe3  18.fxe3  Bb4  18...Bc5 is another possibility.  19.Be2  Bxc3  20.bxc3  Rb1+  21.Rd1  Rb2  22.Rd2  Black could repeat, but  White has tried   22.Rf1  in practice, but only Black can be better after  22...Rxa2  23.Rf5  Re8=+  22...Rgb8=∞  gives Black excellent compensation with the chance to play for more than equality.  Bb4  18.g3  in one game White played   18.e4?  but  18...Bxc3+  followed by a rook invasion gives Black a winning advantage  g5!?  19.Bg2  Bxc3+!  again breaking through.  20.Rxc3   20.bxc3?  Rb1+  21.Kd2  Rd8+  mates!  Rxb2=+  when Black's active pieces give him the edge. }
16... Rxb2 17. Bh3
{ The best try. White gains time by attacking the d7-knight.  There is no time for   17.gxf4?  Bb4  18.Rc1  Nc5-+  when the dual threeats of ...Ne4 and ...Na4 are decisive.   17.Bg2  Rc2!  18.Ne4  Bb4+  19.Kf1  Rf8=+  is nice for Black. }
17... Nf6
{ Black has also tried   17...Nc5  18.O-O  Bd6  which is fine, but I prefer to keep the a3-f8 diagonal open for our bishop. }
18. O-O { There is still no time for   18.gxf4?  Bb4-+ } 18... Bb4 19. Rc1 Rd8
{ Planning to come in to d2. } 20. Bg2
{ White looks for counterplay against the c6-pawn.   20.gxf4  Rdd2  Black can always take on c3 to regain the pawn, but ...Rbc2 is an even stronger idea.   20...Bxc3!  21.Rxc3  Nd5=  was suggested by Kotronias  21.a3!?  Bxc3  White's idea was 21...Bxa3?! 22.Nb1!  22.Rxc3  Ne4!  This is the most active and it gains a tempo. Black is under a little pressure after 22...Rxe2 23.Rfc1 Rb6 24.Bg2. Now  23.Rc4  Rxe2  24.Rfc1  Nxf2  25.Rxc6+  Kd8=  is likely to end in some kind of perpetual check. }
20... Rdd2
{ Still delaying the exchange on g3! If 20...fxg3 21.hxg3 Rdd2 White has 22.Nd1!? Rbc3 23.Ne3 with a better pawn structure. }
21. gxf4
{ After   21.a3  Bxc3  22.Rxc3  Rdc2!?  sets a little trap.  23.Rxc2   23.Rc1?!  Rxc3  24.Rxc3  Rb1+  25.Bf1  Ne4  caused all kinds of problems. For example  26.Rd3  Nc5  27.Rf3  Nb3  28.Rd3  c5-+  Rxc2= }
21... Rbc2 { Black has some initiative and White was wise to bail out with }
22. Ne4 Rxe2 23. Nxf6 gxf6 24. Rxc2 Rxc2 25. Be4
{ an important point. White gets a passed pawn of his own. Without this move Black would be much better. }
